Lullaby

5
00:00:31.960 --> 00:00:35.040
Soul
Surrendering your soul

6
00:00:35.080 --> 00:00:38.480
The heart in you not whole

7
00:00:38.560 --> 00:00:42.120
For love

8
00:00:42.200 --> 00:00:46.400
For love

9
00:00:49.400 --> 00:00:55.000
Walked out

10
00:00:55.080 --> 00:01:00.240
Cast into the dark

11
00:01:02.160 --> 00:01:08.960
Branded with a mark

12
00:01:09.000 --> 00:01:12.640
Of shame

13
00:01:12.720 --> 00:01:18.080
Of Cain

14
00:01:21.520 --> 00:01:23.640
lf I could just go back.

15
00:01:24.720 --> 00:01:27.000
If I could rub everything out.

16
00:01:27.080 --> 00:01:29.040
starting with myself.

17
00:01:30.920 --> 00:01:33.440
Starting with borrowing
A jacket.

18
00:01:33.520 --> 00:01:37.120
Oh. such fleeting
paradise

19
00:01:37.160 --> 00:01:40.640
Such innocent
delight

20
00:01:40.720 --> 00:01:45.080
To love

21
00:01:45.160 --> 00:01:47.840
Be loved

22
00:01:47.920 --> 00:01:52.560
A lullaby

23
00:01:53.600 --> 00:02:01.560
Then silence

24
00:02:04.880 --> 00:02:07.920
- Frances. that was lovely.
- I'm so glad. Thank you.

25
00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:10.640
Congratulations.

26
00:02:10.720 --> 00:02:13.280
Marvelous.
Most enjoyable.

27
00:02:13.320 --> 00:02:15.720
Herbert Greenleaf.
My wife. Emily.

28
00:02:15.800 --> 00:02:17.160
Thank you.
Tom Ripley.

29
00:02:17.240 --> 00:02:19.480
- How do you do?
- You were at Princeton.

30
00:02:19.560 --> 00:02:22.320
Most likely you'll know our son.
Dick. Dickie Greenleaf.

31
00:02:22.400 --> 00:02:24.240
I couldn 't help
Noticing your jacket.

32
00:02:24.320 --> 00:02:26.000
Yes.

33
00:02:26.080 --> 00:02:29.000
Class of'56.

34
00:02:29.080 --> 00:02:31.800
How is Dickie?

35
00:02:31.880 --> 00:02:34.120
We've enjoyed meeting you.

36
00:02:34.200 --> 00:02:36.600
I do hope that you'll
come out and see us.

37
00:02:36.680 --> 00:02:39.560
- Thank you. That's very kind.
- Both of you.

38
00:02:39.640 --> 00:02:42.640
- Herbert?
- Yes. yes. I very much hope so.

39
00:02:42.720 --> 00:02:45.760
Of course. Dickie's idea
of music is jazz.

40
00:02:45.840 --> 00:02:48.080
- Oh. dear.
- He has a saxophone.

41
00:02:48.160 --> 00:02:51.000
To my ear.
jazz is just noise.

42
00:02:51.080 --> 00:02:53.120
Just an insolent noise.

43
00:02:53.160 --> 00:02:56.040
- Very nice to meet you.
- And you.

44
00:02:56.080 --> 00:02:57.920
- Sir.
- We'll see you at the shipyard.

45
00:02:58.000 --> 00:02:59.840
- I hope to.
- Good.

46
00:03:01.400 --> 00:03:03.560
I have to run!
I'm very late!

47
00:03:05.320 --> 00:03:08.200
- Ah. you were great!
- You were great.

48
00:03:08.280 --> 00:03:10.880
Darling couple.
aren't they?

49
00:03:10.920 --> 00:03:13.840
Yes. they are.
Exceptional young man.

50
00:03:15.960 --> 00:03:18.120
- Thanks a lot for the jacket.
- Thanks for filling in for me.

51
00:03:18.200 --> 00:03:20.200
Take care of that wrist.
Bye. Fran.

52
00:03:27.480 --> 00:03:30.280
Believe me.
Buy I.B.M. now. before it splits.

53
00:03:30.360 --> 00:03:32.200
You'll make yourself
a fortune.

54
00:03:32.280 --> 00:03:34.120
You think so?

55
00:04:08.920 --> 00:04:10.760
Sorry.
Sorry.

56
00:04:11.840 --> 00:04:13.680
Sorry.

57
00:04:13.760 --> 00:04:16.960
You've probably
Heard Dickie's been living in Italy.

58
00:04:17.040 --> 00:04:19.640
Mongibello.
South of Naples.

59
00:04:19.720 --> 00:04:21.840
No kind of place
at all.

60
00:04:21.920 --> 00:04:23.760
- Good morning. sir.
- Frank.

61
00:04:23.840 --> 00:04:27.040
Marge.
his young lady.

62
00:04:27.080 --> 00:04:29.200
is supposedly writing
some kind of book.

63
00:04:29.280 --> 00:04:31.120
God only knows
what he does.

64
00:04:31.200 --> 00:04:35.040
By all accounts. they spend the whole
time on the beach or in a sailboat.

65
00:04:35.120 --> 00:04:38.440
That's my son's talent--
spending his allowance.

66
00:04:38.520 --> 00:04:41.720
Could you ever conceive
of going to Italy. Tom?

67
00:04:41.800 --> 00:04:44.960
Persuade my son
to come home?

68
00:04:46.440 --> 00:04:48.280
I'd pay you...

69
00:04:48.360 --> 00:04:51.160
a thousand dollars.

70
00:04:53.320 --> 00:04:56.760
Well. I have always wanted
to go to Europe. sir. but--

71
00:04:56.840 --> 00:05:00.520
Good. Now you can go
for a reason.

72
00:05:15.320 --> 00:05:17.600
Count Basie.

73
00:05:17.680 --> 00:05:20.800
Duke Ellington?
I don't know.

74
00:05:22.720 --> 00:05:25.000
I don't know.

75
00:05:26.880 --> 00:05:29.080
I don't know.

76
00:05:34.960 --> 00:05:37.160
Dizzy Gillespie.

77
00:05:37.240 --> 00:05:40.520
My funny Valentine

78
00:05:40.600 --> 00:05:42.400
My funny Valentine.

79
00:05:42.440 --> 00:05:46.520
-Sweet. funny Valentine

80
00:05:46.600 --> 00:05:49.200
I don't even know
If this is a man or a woman.

81
00:06:06.600 --> 00:06:08.520
Charlie Parker?

82
00:06:08.560 --> 00:06:11.320
Charlie Parker.
I know it. It's Bird.

83
00:06:13.800 --> 00:06:15.960
Yes!

84
00:06:16.040 --> 00:06:17.880
- Ugh.

85
00:06:38.400 --> 00:06:41.360
- Here. I'll take it.
- Thanks.

86
00:06:41.440 --> 00:06:43.480
That thousand bucks
should come in handy.

87
00:06:43.560 --> 00:06:45.440
- Yes. sir.
- I'll get that.

88
00:06:49.920 --> 00:06:54.360
- Thank you.
- Sir. You're gonna have a great trip.

89
00:06:54.440 --> 00:06:57.200
Mr. Greenleaf is personal
friends with the Cunard people.

90
00:07:02.560 --> 00:07:06.280
I can tell you. the Greenleaf name
opens a lot of doors.

91
00:07:41.800 --> 00:07:45.480
- Do you speak English?
- What you name. please?

92
00:07:45.560 --> 00:07:47.720
- Ripley.
- Follow me. No problem.

93
00:07:47.800 --> 00:07:50.560
- Here. Signor Ripley.
- Okay.

94
00:07:51.720 --> 00:07:53.560
Uh. there.
That one.

95
00:07:53.640 --> 00:07:55.640
- This one.
- Wait. is that all? Count them.

96
00:07:55.720 --> 00:07:58.720
Attenzione.
Just one suitcase. Signor Ripley?

97
00:07:58.760 --> 00:08:01.920
- Si.
- Attenzione.

98
00:08:16.720 --> 00:08:19.040
- What's your secret?
- Excuse me?

99
00:08:19.120 --> 00:08:22.120
No. it's just that--
You are American. aren't you?

100
00:08:22.200 --> 00:08:24.200
No. it's just that--

101
00:08:24.280 --> 00:08:28.640
I have so much luggage.
and you're so. um. streamlined.

102
00:08:28.720 --> 00:08:31.000
It's. you know.
humiliating.

103
00:08:33.040 --> 00:08:34.880
I'm Meredith.
by the way.

104
00:08:34.960 --> 00:08:39.320
- Hello. I'm Dickie.
- Meredith Randall.

105
00:08:39.400 --> 00:08:42.360
- Um. Dickie Greenleaf.
- Hello.

106
00:08:44.280 --> 00:08:47.160
You're not
the shipping Greenleafs.

107
00:08:47.240 --> 00:08:49.480
Oh. trying not to be.

108
00:08:49.560 --> 00:08:51.160
Trying to jump ship.

109
00:08:51.240 --> 00:08:54.600
So. uh. did they put
your cases in the wrong pile?

110
00:08:54.680 --> 00:08:58.600
It's just that. uh.
you were in the "R" stand.

111
00:08:58.680 --> 00:09:02.680
I thought
I saw you there.

112
00:09:02.760 --> 00:09:05.600
My father wants me
back in New York.

113
00:09:05.680 --> 00:09:08.360
He builds boats.
I'd rather sail them.

114
00:09:08.400 --> 00:09:10.880
So I travel
under my mother's name.

115
00:09:10.960 --> 00:09:14.200
- Which is--
- Emily.

116
00:09:14.280 --> 00:09:16.360
I'm just kidding.

117
00:09:17.640 --> 00:09:19.720
You know.
the funny thing is.

118
00:09:19.800 --> 00:09:22.200
I'm not Randall either.

119
00:09:23.320 --> 00:09:25.200
I'm Logue.

120
00:09:25.240 --> 00:09:28.160
- As in--
- As in the textile Logues.

121
00:09:28.240 --> 00:09:30.920
Trying to
shrug off the dress.

122
00:09:30.960 --> 00:09:33.000
- I travel under my mother's name too.
- Randall.

123
00:09:33.080 --> 00:09:34.960
Right.

124
00:09:35.000 --> 00:09:37.960
- So. Rome. Rome. Rome.
- Oh.

125
00:09:39.560 --> 00:09:43.160
- We're partners in disguise. Bye.
- Bye.

126
00:10:57.040 --> 00:10:59.240
"The fiancée has
a face. "

127
00:11:22.520 --> 00:11:24.480
Bird.

128
00:11:27.920 --> 00:11:30.440
"This is my face. "

129
00:12:02.400 --> 00:12:05.200
So I guess you didn't
Look at my new chapter.

130
00:12:05.280 --> 00:12:07.240
I will. Marge.
I promise.

131
00:12:07.320 --> 00:12:09.200
It's just been too hot.

132
00:12:18.680 --> 00:12:21.160
If I make dinner at my place tonight.
maybe you could look at it then.

133
00:12:21.200 --> 00:12:23.440
Dickie Greenleaf?

134
00:12:23.520 --> 00:12:26.760
- Who's that?
- It's Tom. Tom Ripley.

135
00:12:26.800 --> 00:12:28.600
Tom Ripley?

136
00:12:28.680 --> 00:12:32.040
- We were at Princeton together.
- Okay.

137
00:12:32.120 --> 00:12:34.800
Did we know each other?

138
00:12:34.880 --> 00:12:37.440
Hello.
Well. I knew you. so...

139
00:12:37.520 --> 00:12:39.400
I suppose
you must have known me.

140
00:12:40.920 --> 00:12:42.800
Princeton's like a fog.

141
00:12:42.840 --> 00:12:46.160
America's like a fog.

142
00:12:46.200 --> 00:12:49.400
This is Marge Sherwood.
Tom-- Sorry. what is it?

143
00:12:49.480 --> 00:12:50.880
- Ripley.
- How do you do?

144
00:12:50.960 --> 00:12:54.200
How do you do. Marge?

145
00:12:54.280 --> 00:12:56.320
- What are you doing in Mongi?
- Nothing.

146
00:12:56.400 --> 00:12:58.240
Nothing much.

147
00:12:58.320 --> 00:13:00.520
Just passing through.

148
00:13:00.600 --> 00:13:03.720
- Passing through?
- Yeah.

149
00:13:03.800 --> 00:13:05.680
You're so white.

150
00:13:07.920 --> 00:13:10.400
Did you ever see a guy
so white. Marge?

151
00:13:10.480 --> 00:13:12.360
Gray. actually.

152
00:13:12.440 --> 00:13:14.840
It's just an undercoat.

153
00:13:14.920 --> 00:13:18.360
- Say again?
- You know. a primer.

154
00:13:20.680 --> 00:13:22.440
That's funny.

155
00:13:22.520 --> 00:13:25.320
Margie likes that
'cause she's so white too.

156
00:13:25.360 --> 00:13:27.400
Yes. I do.
and you're not funny.

157
00:13:27.440 --> 00:13:29.320
You should come and have lunch
with us before you go.

158
00:13:29.360 --> 00:13:32.040
- Yes. Dickie?
- Sure. anytime.

159
00:13:32.080 --> 00:13:34.440
Well.

160
00:13:34.480 --> 00:13:36.360
coincidence.

161
00:13:40.600 --> 00:13:42.800
I don't remember him.

162
00:13:42.880 --> 00:13:44.880
That's so funny.

163
00:13:50.680 --> 00:13:52.840
Silvana! Hey!

164
00:13:54.280 --> 00:13:56.640
I've been looking all over for you.

165
00:13:56.680 --> 00:13:58.480
Where've you been hiding?

166
00:13:58.560 --> 00:14:01.320
Today you're looking for me. Where've
you been the rest of the week?

167
00:14:01.400 --> 00:14:04.640
You're always working.
Come on. Get on.

168
00:14:04.680 --> 00:14:07.400
With the American girl?

169
00:14:07.440 --> 00:14:09.320
- Hold on to me.
- I hate you.

170
00:14:09.360 --> 00:14:12.880
- Huh?
- I hate you!

171
00:14:14.480 --> 00:14:16.360
Did you suddenly forget where I lived?

172
00:14:16.400 --> 00:14:18.480
I know. I'm late.
I'm a swine.

173
00:14:18.560 --> 00:14:20.400
- It's 4:00.
- I just woke up.

174
00:14:20.480 --> 00:14:22.840
- Ohh.
- I'm sorry. I'm sorry.

175
00:14:22.920 --> 00:14:25.480
- You just woke up.
- Fausto and I took the boat out.

176
00:14:25.560 --> 00:14:29.040
We were fishing. and then it was dawn.
and we caught absolutely nothing.

177
00:14:29.120 --> 00:14:33.120
Mmm. yes. well.
we ate everything without you.

178
00:14:33.160 --> 00:14:35.200
- We?
- Yes.

179
00:14:35.280 --> 00:14:38.080
- Tom Ripley's here.
- Who?

180
00:14:40.040 --> 00:14:43.160
- Tom. Hello.
- Hi.

181
00:14:43.240 --> 00:14:45.600
-Hello.
-How are you? Thought you'd disappeared.

182
00:14:45.680 --> 00:14:48.520
- We were gonna send out a search party.
- No.

183
00:14:48.560 --> 00:14:52.600
- No. still here.
- Tom was telling me about his journey.

184
00:14:52.680 --> 00:14:56.480
Made me laugh so hard
I almost got a nosebleed.

185
00:14:56.560 --> 00:15:00.000
- Is that good?
- Shut up.

186
00:15:00.080 --> 00:15:02.920
I'm sorry.
I'm sorry.

187
00:15:02.960 --> 00:15:05.480
I'm despicable.
But I love you.

188
00:15:05.560 --> 00:15:08.360
- Do you love me? Do you love me?
- I'm intruding.

189
00:15:08.440 --> 00:15:10.840
Can you mix
a martini?

190
00:15:12.960 --> 00:15:15.960
- Sure.
- I'll do it.

191
00:15:16.040 --> 00:15:18.840
- Ohh.
- I make a fabulous martini.

192
00:15:23.440 --> 00:15:26.680
Everybody should have
one talent. What's yours?

193
00:15:26.760 --> 00:15:28.760
Forging signatures.

194
00:15:28.840 --> 00:15:31.760
telling lies. impersonating
practically anybody.

195
00:15:31.840 --> 00:15:35.760
That's three. Nobody should have
more than one talent.

196
00:15:36.840 --> 00:15:38.960
Okay.
do an impression.

197
00:15:39.040 --> 00:15:41.440
- Now?
- Yeah.

198
00:15:41.520 --> 00:15:44.480
The only talent my son has...

199
00:15:44.560 --> 00:15:46.920
is for cashing
his allowance.

200
00:15:49.000 --> 00:15:51.240
- What?
- Oh. I like to sail.

201
00:15:51.320 --> 00:15:53.160
Believe me.
I love to sail.

202
00:15:53.200 --> 00:15:55.120
- Instead. I make boats.
- Stop!

203
00:15:55.200 --> 00:15:57.480
- Other people sail them.
- It's too much!

204
00:15:57.520 --> 00:15:59.440
You're making all the hairs
on my neck stand up.

205
00:15:59.520 --> 00:16:02.760
Oh. yes. Jazz.
Oh. jazz. Let's face it.

206
00:16:02.840 --> 00:16:06.240
It's just. uh--
It's just insolent noise.

207
00:16:06.320 --> 00:16:08.240
I feel like he's here.

208
00:16:08.320 --> 00:16:11.600
- Horrible. like the old bastard's here.
- Good.

209
00:16:11.680 --> 00:16:13.480
That's brilliant.

210
00:16:13.520 --> 00:16:16.120
Brilliant!
How do you know him?

211
00:16:16.200 --> 00:16:17.920
Oh. I met him in New York.

212
00:16:17.960 --> 00:16:20.120
Marge!
Marge. this is scary.

213
00:16:20.200 --> 00:16:22.400
You've got to hear this.
Meet my father.

214
00:16:22.440 --> 00:16:24.560
Herbert Richard Greenleaf I.

215
00:16:24.640 --> 00:16:28.360
Pleasure to meet you.
Dickie's made a fine catch.

216
00:16:28.440 --> 00:16:30.880
- Uncanny!
- I know Emily thinks so.

217
00:16:30.920 --> 00:16:33.120
- I don't get it.
- It's uncanny.

218
00:16:33.160 --> 00:16:36.160
Could you ever conceive
of going to Italy. Tom.

219
00:16:36.240 --> 00:16:39.080
and. uh. bringing him back?

220
00:16:39.120 --> 00:16:41.240
- What?
- I'd pay you.

221
00:16:41.320 --> 00:16:43.160
If you would go
to Italy.

222
00:16:43.240 --> 00:16:47.040
persuade my son to come home.
I'd pay you a thousand dollars.

223
00:16:49.600 --> 00:16:51.520
I'm never going back.

224
00:16:51.560 --> 00:16:54.160
To actually hire somebody
to come all the way here...

225
00:16:54.240 --> 00:16:56.080
to drag me back home--

226
00:16:56.160 --> 00:16:58.200
Got to be a little
insane. doesn't he?

227
00:16:58.280 --> 00:17:00.680
- Ciao. Fausto.

228
00:17:04.520 --> 00:17:06.920
- This is Tom.
- Ciao. Tom.

229
00:17:09.080 --> 00:17:11.520
- I'm never going back.
- No. I think--

230
00:17:11.560 --> 00:17:13.480
Your mother. her illness.
I think that's--

231
00:17:13.520 --> 00:17:16.480
It's got nothing to do
with my mother.

232
00:17:16.560 --> 00:17:20.080
She's had leukem--
This is what makes me boil about him.

233
00:17:20.160 --> 00:17:23.600
He wants me back.
He wants me back.

234
00:17:23.680 --> 00:17:25.960
- It's got nothing to do with my mother.
- Look. I don't know--

235
00:17:26.000 --> 00:17:27.880
Go back.
Go back to New York.

236
00:17:27.920 --> 00:17:29.920
Or call him. if you can find
a telephone that works.

237
00:17:29.960 --> 00:17:34.280
and tell him wild horses wouldn't
drag me back to him or his shipyard.

238
00:17:36.640 --> 00:17:39.520
- Hi. Tom.
- Hi.

239
00:17:39.600 --> 00:17:41.800
Marge. Tom's saying good-bye.

240
00:17:41.880 --> 00:17:43.840
Oh. I'll come down.

241
00:17:45.280 --> 00:17:47.600
So. uh. did you
speak to my father?

242
00:17:47.680 --> 00:17:49.800
Oh. you were right...
about the telephones.

243
00:17:49.880 --> 00:17:51.720
- I told you.
- There are no lines.

244
00:17:51.800 --> 00:17:54.440
- There's some problem.
- That's Italy.

245
00:17:56.080 --> 00:18:00.040
Tom. You're off?
What are your plans?

246
00:18:00.120 --> 00:18:02.440
Oh. back. I suppose.
as slow as I can. Oh!

247
00:18:03.200 --> 00:18:06.040
This bag!

248
00:18:07.400 --> 00:18:10.440
Hey.
You like jazz.

249
00:18:10.520 --> 00:18:12.120
I love jazz.

250
00:18:14.560 --> 00:18:16.440
This is the best.

251
00:18:16.480 --> 00:18:19.480
Baker. Rollins.

252
00:18:19.520 --> 00:18:22.600
Marge says she likes jazz.
but she thinks Glenn Miller's jazz.

253
00:18:22.680 --> 00:18:24.560
