496
00:37:08.040 --> 00:37:10.360
God. A corduroy jacket in Italy.

497
00:37:10.440 --> 00:37:12.280
- Good morning. Tom.
- Morning.

498
00:37:12.360 --> 00:37:14.960
- Come join us.

499
00:37:16.800 --> 00:37:20.640
Hey. I want this job
of yours. Tommy.

500
00:37:20.720 --> 00:37:23.520
I was just saying.
you live in Italy.

501
00:37:23.600 --> 00:37:27.000
you stay at Dickie's house.
you eat Dickie's food.

502
00:37:27.080 --> 00:37:31.760
you wear his clothes.
and his father picks up the tab.

503
00:37:31.800 --> 00:37:35.120
If you get bored.

504
00:37:35.200 --> 00:37:38.560
you let me know.
'cause I'll do it.

505
00:37:38.640 --> 00:37:41.360
- I'll do it.
- To the mainland!

506
00:37:45.240 --> 00:37:48.360
You really should go in.
It's marvellous.

507
00:37:48.400 --> 00:37:51.400
I'm fine.

508
00:38:00.560 --> 00:38:02.480
Are you okay?

509
00:38:03.520 --> 00:38:05.520
Sure.

510
00:38:09.520 --> 00:38:12.120
The thing with Dickie--

511
00:38:12.200 --> 00:38:17.000
It's like the sun shines
on you. and it's glorious.

512
00:38:18.440 --> 00:38:21.840
And then he forgets you
and it's very. very cold.

513
00:38:21.920 --> 00:38:23.760
So I'm learning.

514
00:38:23.840 --> 00:38:27.200
When you have his attention. you feel
you're the only person in the world.

515
00:38:27.280 --> 00:38:29.880
That's why
everybody loves him.

516
00:38:29.960 --> 00:38:33.520
It's always the same. Whenever
someone new comes into his life--

517
00:38:33.600 --> 00:38:36.040
Freddie. Fausto.
Peter Smith-Kingsley.

518
00:38:36.120 --> 00:38:38.360
He's wonderful.
Have you met him?

519
00:38:40.760 --> 00:38:43.120
Especially you.

520
00:38:47.440 --> 00:38:50.120
And that's just the boys.

521
00:38:57.000 --> 00:39:00.120
Come get him!
Come get him!

522
00:39:00.200 --> 00:39:02.040
Tell me. why is it
that when men play.

523
00:39:02.120 --> 00:39:04.560
they always play
at killing each other?

524
00:39:04.640 --> 00:39:07.640
He's drowning me!
He's drowning me!

525
00:39:09.520 --> 00:39:13.240
- I'm sorry about Cortina. by the way.
- What about Cortina?

526
00:39:15.600 --> 00:39:18.360
Didn't--
Didn't-Didn't Dick say?

527
00:39:20.000 --> 00:39:22.800
He spoke to Freddie.
and-and apparently...

528
00:39:22.880 --> 00:39:24.720
it's not going
to work out.

529
00:39:26.440 --> 00:39:28.760
It's because
everyone else can ski.

530
00:39:28.840 --> 00:39:31.000
and it affects
where you stay. and--

531
00:39:38.160 --> 00:39:40.520
Come on. Freddie.

532
00:39:40.600 --> 00:39:43.080
At least stick around for
the Festival of the Madonna.

533
00:39:43.160 --> 00:39:45.640
- The whole town comes out--
- I don't think so.

534
00:39:45.720 --> 00:39:50.200
I have my own. uh. Madonna backin Rome.
Why don't you come back with me?

535
00:39:50.280 --> 00:39:52.680
A lot of ladies.
Ooh.

536
00:39:58.120 --> 00:40:00.200
- Oh. God.
- You want to take over?

537
00:40:00.280 --> 00:40:02.160
Yeah. sure.

538
00:40:02.200 --> 00:40:05.040
Just point her at Capri.
Avoid the rocks.

539
00:40:05.080 --> 00:40:07.440
Where are you going?

540
00:40:07.520 --> 00:40:09.440
Marge maintenance.

541
00:40:09.520 --> 00:40:11.360
Aye-aye.

542
00:40:31.640 --> 00:40:33.520
Don't.

543
00:40:46.560 --> 00:40:48.520
- Dickie--

544
00:40:50.520 --> 00:40:54.160
Tommy.
How's the peeping?

545
00:40:55.240 --> 00:40:59.240
Tommy.
how's the peeping?

546
00:41:01.120 --> 00:41:03.200
Tommy. Tommy.
Tommy. Tommy. Tommy.

547
00:42:50.640 --> 00:42:52.520
Is someone getting
an ambulance?

548
00:42:57.160 --> 00:43:00.440
- Is someone getting an ambulance?

549
00:43:27.840 --> 00:43:30.600
What's the fight about?
That's her fiancé. isn't it?

550
00:43:30.680 --> 00:43:35.360
- I don't know. Why are you asking me?
- Are they blaming him?

551
00:43:35.400 --> 00:43:38.920
How can it take an hour
to find an ambulance?

552
00:43:39.000 --> 00:43:41.400
She was already dead. darling.
wasn't she? So I suppose--

553
00:43:41.480 --> 00:43:45.800
I don't know why people say
this country is civilized.

554
00:43:45.880 --> 00:43:48.880
- Dickie!
- It isn't. It's fucking primitive.

555
00:43:50.440 --> 00:43:52.760
I'll go see
what's the matter.

556
00:43:52.800 --> 00:43:54.680
I'll go.

557
00:44:10.560 --> 00:44:12.480
I know why you're upset.

558
00:44:15.040 --> 00:44:17.480
I know about
Silvana. Dickie.

559
00:44:20.080 --> 00:44:22.120
I know about
you and Silvana.

560
00:44:22.200 --> 00:44:24.600
What about us?

561
00:44:27.600 --> 00:44:31.000
You don't have
to clean up! Really!

562
00:44:38.400 --> 00:44:41.040
- Like what?
- Forget it.

563
00:44:43.080 --> 00:44:45.440
She was pregnant.
Did you know that?

564
00:44:49.800 --> 00:44:52.760
Silvana was pregnant.

565
00:44:54.000 --> 00:44:56.480
Do you know what that means
in a place like this?

566
00:44:56.560 --> 00:44:59.360
I'm prepared
to take the blame.

567
00:44:59.440 --> 00:45:03.200
- What are you talking about?
- You've been so good to me.

568
00:45:03.240 --> 00:45:07.800
You're the brother I never had.
I'm the brother you never had.

569
00:45:07.840 --> 00:45:10.480
I would do anything
For you. Dickie.

570
00:45:12.680 --> 00:45:14.680
She came to me for help.

571
00:45:14.760 --> 00:45:16.800
She needed money.

572
00:45:19.680 --> 00:45:23.960
I didn't help her.
I didn't help her.

573
00:45:24.000 --> 00:45:28.160
Now she's drowned herself.
And it's my fault.

574
00:45:35.200 --> 00:45:37.040
I'm not going
to say anything--

575
00:45:37.120 --> 00:45:40.120
to Marge. to the police
or anybody.

576
00:45:40.160 --> 00:45:43.080
It's a secret
between us. Dickie.

577
00:45:45.160 --> 00:45:47.040
And I'll keep it.

578
00:45:48.520 --> 00:45:50.960
"Dear Tom.
In view of the fact Dickie shows...

579
00:45:51.040 --> 00:45:55.640
no more signs of coming home than
before you went--" blah. blah. blah--

580
00:45:55.680 --> 00:45:58.360
Um--

581
00:45:58.400 --> 00:46:00.920
"l hope that the trip has
afforded you some pleasure...

582
00:46:01.000 --> 00:46:04.080
despite the failure
of its main objective.

583
00:46:04.160 --> 00:46:08.440
You no longer should consider yourself
obligated to us in any way."

584
00:46:08.520 --> 00:46:10.440
Can't blame him.

585
00:46:10.520 --> 00:46:12.520
You could hardly expect this
To go on forever. Tom.

586
00:46:12.600 --> 00:46:15.000
Well. you can write again.

587
00:46:15.040 --> 00:46:17.840
- Especially now we're brothers.
- I can't.

588
00:46:17.920 --> 00:46:19.960
How can l.
in all decency.

589
00:46:20.000 --> 00:46:22.640
You said it yourself.
It's my dad's money you're spending.

590
00:46:22.720 --> 00:46:26.680
We've had a great run
though. haven't we?

591
00:46:26.720 --> 00:46:30.520
Well. we'll still go to Venice.
We could stick to that plan.

592
00:46:30.560 --> 00:46:32.560
I don't think so. Tom.

593
00:46:32.640 --> 00:46:35.120
You can't pay
You rown way. can you?

594
00:46:35.200 --> 00:46:39.400
It's time we all moved on.

595
00:46:39.480 --> 00:46:43.520
I'm sick of Mongi.
Especially now. with everything--

596
00:46:43.600 --> 00:46:45.480
I really want to move
to the north.

597
00:46:45.560 --> 00:46:47.960
I need to check out
San Remo next week.

598
00:46:48.040 --> 00:46:50.000
Find somewhere new
to keep the boat.

599
00:46:50.080 --> 00:46:53.320
It would be great. though.
if you came with me to San Remo.

600
00:46:53.400 --> 00:46:56.760
There's a great jazz festival.
We could say good-bye in style.

601
00:46:56.800 --> 00:46:59.280
What do you think?

602
00:46:59.360 --> 00:47:02.000
Our last trip!

603
00:47:07.360 --> 00:47:09.200
Sure.

604
00:48:01.280 --> 00:48:03.480
Why do you do
that thing with your neck?

605
00:48:03.520 --> 00:48:05.400
What thing?

606
00:48:07.480 --> 00:48:10.720
On trains. you always
do that thing.

607
00:48:14.600 --> 00:48:17.360
Spooky.

608
00:48:17.440 --> 00:48:21.120
Spook-- k-k--
k-k-- k-k--

609
00:48:25.000 --> 00:48:26.880
Spooky.

610
00:48:47.040 --> 00:48:48.920
Oh!

611
00:48:48.960 --> 00:48:52.600
Didn't I tell you
San Remo was crazy?

612
00:48:52.640 --> 00:48:55.360
This is more like it!
Come on!

613
00:49:04.800 --> 00:49:07.200
Grazie.

614
00:49:07.280 --> 00:49:10.320
To Mongibello
and the happiest days of my life.

615
00:49:10.400 --> 00:49:12.880
To Mongi.
You're cheerful tonight.

616
00:49:12.960 --> 00:49:15.280
I'm suddenly quite happy
to be going back.

617
00:49:15.360 --> 00:49:18.000
Did I know you
at Princeton. Tom?

618
00:49:18.080 --> 00:49:20.640
I don't think I did.
did I?

619
00:49:20.720 --> 00:49:23.760
- Why are you asking all of a sudden?
- No reason.

620
00:49:23.840 --> 00:49:27.240
Because you're leaving. I guess.
I don't think you were there.

621
00:49:28.320 --> 00:49:31.320
- Why?
- I mean it as a compliment.

622
00:49:31.400 --> 00:49:33.280
You've got
such great taste.

623
00:49:33.320 --> 00:49:37.320
Most of the thugs at Princeton
had tasted everything and had no taste.

624
00:49:37.400 --> 00:49:42.200
I used to say.
"the cream of America: rich and thick."

625
00:49:42.280 --> 00:49:44.280
Freddie's
the perfect example.

626
00:49:44.360 --> 00:49:46.840
Then I'll take it
as a compliment.

627
00:49:46.920 --> 00:49:48.800
I knew it!
I knew it.

628
00:49:48.880 --> 00:49:51.640
Marge and I had a bet.

629
00:49:59.640 --> 00:50:01.440
Do you even like jazz.

630
00:50:01.520 --> 00:50:03.680
or was that
for my benefit?

631
00:50:03.800 --> 00:50:06.360
- I've gotten to like it.
- Oh. yes!

632
00:50:07.960 --> 00:50:10.760
I've gotten to like everything
about the way you live.

633
00:50:10.800 --> 00:50:12.960
It's one big love affair.

634
00:50:15.000 --> 00:50:17.040
If you knew my life
back home in New York--

635
00:50:17.120 --> 00:50:19.120
I'm thinkin'
of givin' up the sax.

636
00:50:19.200 --> 00:50:21.240
What do you think
about the drums?

637
00:50:21.320 --> 00:50:24.400
- What?
- So cool.

638
00:50:24.480 --> 00:50:27.280
I'm gonna rent a boat tomorrow.
take a look around.

639
00:50:28.280 --> 00:50:30.760
This is how I found
my place in Mongi.

640
00:50:30.800 --> 00:50:33.720
Took a boat out...

641
00:50:33.800 --> 00:50:35.720
around the bay.

642
00:50:35.760 --> 00:50:38.240
first thing I liked.

643
00:50:38.320 --> 00:50:40.160
I got it.

644
00:50:41.480 --> 00:50:45.560
- Whoa!
- Come on. Dickie. Don't go crazy.

645
00:50:45.640 --> 00:50:48.040
- Dickie. Slow down!
- Hold on.

646
00:50:48.080 --> 00:50:50.000
Wait a minute!
It's gonna tip! Oh. God!

647
00:50:50.080 --> 00:50:53.480
Stop it! Somebody!
Somebody! Stop it!

648
00:50:56.880 --> 00:50:58.920
Oh. I love it here!

649
00:50:59.000 --> 00:51:01.440
I love it here!
I'm gonna move here!

650
00:51:01.520 --> 00:51:04.000
Beautiful.

651
00:51:08.240 --> 00:51:11.200
I want to tell you
my plan.

652
00:51:11.280 --> 00:51:14.040
- So tell me.
- Well. I thought...

653
00:51:14.120 --> 00:51:16.880
I'd come back in the new year
under my own steam.

654
00:51:16.960 --> 00:51:20.000
- Really? To Italy?
- Of course.

655
00:51:20.080 --> 00:51:23.400
And I figured.
just for argument's sake.

656
00:51:23.480 --> 00:51:25.440
say I got a place.

657
00:51:25.520 --> 00:51:27.880
Or say we split
the rent on a house.

658
00:51:27.920 --> 00:51:30.080
I could get a job.
or. better still.

659
00:51:30.160 --> 00:51:31.920
if I got a place in Rome.
and then when we're there.

660
00:51:32.000 --> 00:51:34.680
we could be there. and when we're here.
we could be here.

661
00:51:34.760 --> 00:51:39.120
- I don't think so.
- Particularly with the Marge problem.

662
00:51:39.200 --> 00:51:41.160
You just blame me.

663
00:51:42.360 --> 00:51:46.640
- Marge and I are getting married.
- How?

664
00:51:46.680 --> 00:51:50.480
- How?
- Yesterday. you were ogling girls.

665
00:51:50.560 --> 00:51:52.400
Today you're getting married?
That's absurd.

666
00:51:54.400 --> 00:51:58.200
- I love Marge.
- You love me. You're not marrying me.

667
00:51:58.280 --> 00:52:00.920
- Tom. I don't love you.
- No. I don't mean that as a threat.

668
00:52:01.000 --> 00:52:03.960
To be honest. I'm-I'm a little
relieved you're going.

669
00:52:04.040 --> 00:52:06.680
I think we've seen enough
Of each other for a while.

670
00:52:11.320 --> 00:52:14.120
- What?
- You can be a leech!

671
00:52:14.160 --> 00:52:16.040
You know that!

672
00:52:18.000 --> 00:52:21.000
And... it's boring.

673
00:52:23.520 --> 00:52:26.400
You can be quite boring.

674
00:52:37.880 --> 00:52:40.040
The funny thing is.
I'm not pretending...

675
00:52:40.080 --> 00:52:42.480
to be somebody else.
and you are.

676
00:52:42.520 --> 00:52:45.560
-Boring.
-I've been absolutely honest with you...

677
00:52:45.640 --> 00:52:47.480
about my feelings.

678
00:52:47.560 --> 00:52:50.120
- Boring.
- But you-- First of all.

679
00:52:50.160 --> 00:52:52.040
I know there's something.

680
00:52:52.080 --> 00:52:54.960
That evening. when we played chess.
for instance. it was obvious.

681
00:52:55.000 --> 00:52:58.320
- What evening?
- It's too dangerous for you to take on.

682
00:52:58.360 --> 00:53:00.360
Oh. no. no.
We're brothers.

683
00:53:00.400 --> 00:53:04.920
Hey. And then you do this sordid thing
with Marge-- fucking her...

684
00:53:05.000 --> 00:53:06.760
on the boat. while we
all have to listen.

685
00:53:06.800 --> 00:53:08.720
which was
excruciating.

686
00:53:08.760 --> 00:53:11.800
And you follow your cock around like a--
And now you're getting married.

687
00:53:11.880 --> 00:53:14.120
No. I'm bewildered.
Forgive me.

688
00:53:14.160 --> 00:53:16.520
You're lying to Marge and then
you're getting married to her.

689
00:53:16.560 --> 00:53:20.720
You're knocking up Sylvana. ruining
everybody-- You want to play the sax.

690
00:53:20.800 --> 00:53:23.120
You want to play the drums. Which is it.
Dickie? What are you actually--

691
00:53:24.960 --> 00:53:28.560
Who are you? Huh?
Some third-class mooch? Who are you?

692
00:53:28.640 --> 00:53:30.520
Who are you to say
anything to me?

693
00:53:30.600 --> 00:53:33.040
Who are you
to tell me anything?

694
00:53:33.120 --> 00:53:36.080
Actually. I really. really do
not want to be on this boat with you.

695
00:53:36.160 --> 00:53:38.480
- I can't move without you moving.
- Shut up. Shut up.

696
00:53:38.560 --> 00:53:41.840
It gives me the creeps.
You give me the creeps.

697
00:53:41.920 --> 00:53:43.800
- You shut up.
- I can't move without "Dickie. Dickie."

698
00:53:43.880 --> 00:53:45.840
Ike a little girl
all the time.

699
00:53:45.920 --> 00:53:47.640
Shut up!

700
00:53:49.160 --> 00:53:51.760
Oh. God. Dickie.

701
00:53:51.840 --> 00:53:54.480
- God's sake.
- Oh-- Oh God!

702
00:53:56.560 --> 00:53:58.920
Okay. Okay.

703
00:53:59.000 --> 00:54:01.040
We have to get you-- Okay--

704
00:54:03.040 --> 00:54:05.600
I'm gonna kill you!
Kill you!

705
00:54:08.560 --> 00:54:10.800
You're dead!

706
00:54:17.400 --> 00:54:20.080
Stop! Stop!
Please! Please!

707
00:54:20.160 --> 00:54:24.040
- Stop it! Stop!

708
00:54:26.000 --> 00:54:27.880
- Dickie. let go!
- I'll kill you!

709
00:54:33.360 --> 00:54:36.880
Stop! Stop!
Stop!

710
00:54:36.960 --> 00:54:39.640
Stop! Stop!
Stop!

711
00:56:37.960 --> 00:56:40.240
Hi. Can I have
my key. please?

712
00:56:40.320 --> 00:56:42.200
Of course.

713
00:56:42.280 --> 00:56:45.600
You must be very cold.
Uh. Signor Greenleaf. yes?

714
00:56:45.680 --> 00:56:47.520
No. I'm--

715
00:57:54.400 --> 00:57:57.760
- Hello. Marge.

716
00:57:57.840 --> 00:58:00.360
Tom!

717
00:58:00.400 --> 00:58:02.400
You startled me!

718
00:58:02.480 --> 00:58:05.520
- Sorry. How are you?
- You're back!

719
00:58:05.600 --> 00:58:07.960
- Your book going well?
- Yes.

720
00:58:08.040 --> 00:58:10.920
I'm on a good streak.
Thank you.

721
00:58:11.000 --> 00:58:14.440
I was just...
looking at you. So quiet.

722
00:58:14.520 --> 00:58:17.360
Where's Dickie?

723
00:58:20.520 --> 00:58:23.400
I think he's planning on staying
in Rome for a few days.

724
00:58:23.480 --> 00:58:27.080
Rome? Ahh.
Did he say why?

725
00:58:27.160 --> 00:58:30.040
I don't understand Dickie.
Your guess is as good as mine.

726
00:58:30.120 --> 00:58:32.000
What does that mean?

727
00:58:32.080 --> 00:58:36.400
Oh. one day I'm invited skiing.
the next day I'm not.

728
00:58:38.480 --> 00:58:42.600
One day. we're one family.
then the next day he wants to be alone.

729
00:58:42.640 --> 00:58:44.520
You tell me.

730
00:58:44.560 --> 00:58:47.040
Is that what he said?
He wants to be alone?

731
00:58:47.120 --> 00:58:51.360
He was thinking of you.
He asked me to deliver this.

732
00:58:51.440 --> 00:58:54.640
Thank you.

733
00:58:54.720 --> 00:58:56.680
He knows
I love this.

734
00:58:58.400 --> 00:59:01.320
- But why it couldn't have waited. I--
- Errand number one.:

735
00:59:01.400 --> 00:59:03.840
deliver Marge's perfume.

736
00:59:03.920 --> 00:59:06.360
Errand number two:

737
00:59:06.440 --> 00:59:09.480
pack some clothes
and his precious saxophone.

738
00:59:11.080 --> 00:59:12.960
How long is he staying for?

739
00:59:13.040 --> 00:59:16.320
Search me.
I guess we're abandoned.

740
00:59:41.600 --> 00:59:43.880
Goddamn it!

741
00:59:45.200 --> 00:59:47.040
Are you okay?

742
00:59:57.160 --> 01:00:00.360
There was a letter from Dickie
in with my perfume.

743
01:00:02.360 --> 01:00:05.880
You realize it's more
than just a few days.

744
01:00:05.960 --> 01:00:09.800
He's thinking of moving to Rome.

745
01:00:09.840 --> 01:00:12.160
The thing is.

746
01:00:12.240 --> 01:00:14.800
the night before
he left. we--

747
01:00:14.880 --> 01:00:16.880
we talked about
moving together...

748
01:00:18.520 --> 01:00:20.520
somewhere north.
and I suppose I...

749
01:00:23.040 --> 01:00:26.160
put some pressure on him
about getting married.

750
01:00:28.080 --> 01:00:30.160
I just--

751
01:00:32.080 --> 01:00:34.280
I just might have
scared him off.

752
01:00:39.720 --> 01:00:42.280
There's a side to him...

753
01:00:42.320 --> 01:00:45.520
when our heads
are on the pillow...

754
01:00:45.600 --> 01:00:48.840
I know no one else sees
that's so tender.

755
01:00:50.800 --> 01:00:53.960
I think I should come with you
to Rome and confront him.

756
01:01:00.040 --> 01:01:02.800
He hates
being confronted.

757
01:01:04.520 --> 01:01:06.640
I think you're right.

758
01:01:15.240 --> 01:01:17.280
Grazie.
Checking in.

759
01:01:25.360 --> 01:01:27.240
Checking in.

760
01:01:27.280 --> 01:01:31.240
- Signor Ripley?
- It's me.

761
01:01:33.320 --> 01:01:36.320
Signor Greenleaf.

762
01:01:36.360 --> 01:01:38.760
Of course.
Welcome back.

763
01:01:38.840 --> 01:01:41.120
Thank you.

764
01:01:57.880 --> 01:01:59.720
Pronto?

765
01:01:59.800 --> 01:02:03.040
Yes. I'd like to telephone
the Hotel Goldoni.

766
01:02:03.080 --> 01:02:07.520
- Si. signor.
- I want to speak to Thomas Ripley.

767
01:02:07.560 --> 01:02:10.400
- Ripley? Subito.
- Yes. Grazie.

768
01:02:18.040 --> 01:02:22.840
- Pronto.

769
01:02:22.920 --> 01:02:24.760
Signor Greenleaf.
Signor Ripley's not there.

770
01:02:24.840 --> 01:02:26.880
- He's not there?
- No. signor.

771
01:02:26.920 --> 01:02:29.560
Well. I would like
to leave a message.

772
01:02:29.640 --> 01:02:31.800
- He's not there? I'll leave a message.
- No. signor.

773
01:02:31.880 --> 01:02:33.920
- Got your call.
- Got your call.

774
01:02:33.960 --> 01:02:35.840
- Dinner tonight...
- Dinner tonight...

775
01:02:35.880 --> 01:02:37.760
- sounds fine.
- sounds fine.

776
01:02:37.800 --> 01:02:41.160
- Ripley. Ripley.
- Ripley.

777
01:02:41.240 --> 01:02:44.600
- Dickie Greenleaf.
- Dickie Greenleaf.

778
01:02:44.680 --> 01:02:47.520
- Yes. Greenleaf.
- Greenleaf.

779
01:02:47.600 --> 01:02:49.640
At the Grand.

780
01:02:49.720 --> 01:02:53.000
And I'd like to have
this wallet embossed.

781
01:02:53.080 --> 01:02:54.920
I don't know
the word in Italian.

782
01:02:55.000 --> 01:02:56.920
Embossed. Of course.
Signor Greenleaf.

783
01:02:57.000 --> 01:02:58.920
Thank you.

784
01:03:02.480 --> 01:03:06.040
Dickie!
It's--

785
01:03:09.000 --> 01:03:10.840
- Oh. my gosh.
- Meredith.

786
01:03:10.920 --> 01:03:12.760
- Ciao!
- Ciao. Come in. Come in.

787
01:03:12.840 --> 01:03:15.360
But you're going skiing
with those Yankees. aren't you?

788
01:03:15.440 --> 01:03:19.920
- What?
- At Christmas. To Cortina.

789
01:03:20.000 --> 01:03:21.880
- With Freddie Miles.
- How did you know that?

790
01:03:21.960 --> 01:03:25.800
Oh! Everybody
knows Freddie Miles.

791
01:03:28.400 --> 01:03:30.320
Is Freddie in Rome?

792
01:03:30.400 --> 01:03:32.240
- Now?
- Yeah.

793
01:03:32.320 --> 01:03:34.560
Oh. I don't think so.

794
01:03:34.640 --> 01:03:38.880
But l-- But I've met him.
Of course. and we've chatted.

795
01:03:38.920 --> 01:03:42.400
And I know about you...

796
01:03:42.480 --> 01:03:44.960
and Marge in Mongi.

797
01:03:45.040 --> 01:03:48.120
What an unreliable
rat you are.

798
01:03:48.200 --> 01:03:50.360
Well. Freddie said
you were a rat.

799
01:03:50.440 --> 01:03:52.640
And I thought
to myself.

800
01:03:52.680 --> 01:03:55.680
"Ah. now I know why
he travels under 'R.'"

801
01:03:55.760 --> 01:03:58.000
I've left Marge.
Meredith.

802
01:03:58.080 --> 01:04:00.200
And Mongi.

803
01:04:00.280 --> 01:04:03.400
- So the rat's here in Rome.
- Oh. I'm sorry.

804
01:04:03.480 --> 01:04:06.480
Oh. don't be sorry. no.
I've never been happier.

805
01:04:06.560 --> 01:04:09.720
I-- I feel like
I've been handed a new life.

806
01:04:09.800 --> 01:04:13.520
The truth is that if you've had money
your entire life.

807
01:04:13.600 --> 01:04:16.760
either you despise it.
which we do-- agreed?

808
01:04:16.840 --> 01:04:19.680
You're only truly comfortable
around other people...

809
01:04:19.720 --> 01:04:22.680
who have it
and despise it.

810
01:04:22.760 --> 01:04:24.600
I know.

811
01:04:26.040 --> 01:04:28.560
I've never admitted that
to anyone.

812
01:04:33.880 --> 01:04:37.000
Because my friend
Mr. Greenleaf. Signor Greenleaf and I.

813
01:04:37.080 --> 01:04:38.920
are on a little spending spree.

814
01:04:39.000 --> 01:04:42.800
- I see.
- We're behaving very badly.

815
01:04:42.880 --> 01:04:47.160
Oh. I love Italian money. So dark.
Doesn't make you feel guilty.

816
01:04:47.240 --> 01:04:49.080
- Gr-r-razie.
- Thank you.

817
01:04:59.240 --> 01:05:02.600
I don't want too many large bills.
No one will change them.

818
01:05:02.680 --> 01:05:04.680
Tutto bene.
Signor Greenleaf.

819
01:05:19.880 --> 01:05:23.360
- I really like this too.
- I think I'm having that too.

820
01:05:29.480 --> 01:05:31.840
- Tomorrow.

821
01:05:36.480 --> 01:05:38.840
- Arrivederci.
- Arrivederci. Oops!

822
01:05:40.040 --> 01:05:41.880
- Ciao.
- Ciao.

823
01:05:47.160 --> 01:05:51.400
I know you're a jazz fiend.
but do you absolutely hate the opera?

824
01:05:54.480 --> 01:05:57.280
I've--
I've...

825
01:05:57.320 --> 01:06:00.800
been trying to give
my tickets away.

826
01:06:00.880 --> 01:06:05.160
It's tomorrow. But if
you were prepared to be dragged--

827
01:06:06.600 --> 01:06:08.680
You could drag me.

828
01:07:52.520 --> 01:07:56.080
Feodor Chaliapin.
It's the whole Russian baritone.

829
01:07:56.160 --> 01:07:59.400
Thank you so much
for inviting me tonight.

830
01:07:59.480 --> 01:08:03.160
Can you bear it?
We hear you are a friend of Freddie's.

831
01:08:03.240 --> 01:08:06.280
He has "l hate opera"
tattooed on his chest.

832
01:08:06.360 --> 01:08:08.760
There's room for a whole
libretto on Freddie's chest.

833
01:08:10.760 --> 01:08:13.000
I'm sure
we've met before.

834
01:08:13.080 --> 01:08:15.880
I was sure we'd met before.
Weren't you. Ted?

835
01:08:15.960 --> 01:08:17.920
Dick is Herbert
Greenleaf's boy.

836
01:08:17.960 --> 01:08:20.440
- I know.
- Yes. I think we have.

837
01:08:20.520 --> 01:08:24.440
One minute you people are children.
and the next you're getting tattooed.

838
01:08:26.320 --> 01:08:28.800
- Cheers.
- Cheers.

839
01:08:30.800 --> 01:08:32.680
Cheers.

840
01:08:36.800 --> 01:08:39.120
- Excuse me.
- Prego.

841
01:08:39.200 --> 01:08:41.440
Oh!
Excuse me.

842
01:08:41.520 --> 01:08:43.680
- Hello.
- Hello.

843
01:08:45.120 --> 01:08:46.960
- Tom!
- Marge!

844
01:08:47.040 --> 01:08:50.040
How are you?
What are you doing in Rome?

845
01:08:50.120 --> 01:08:53.600
- Is he here? Are you with Dickie?
- No. Um. no.

846
01:08:53.680 --> 01:08:56.640
Um. hello.
Um. I'm Tom Ripley.

847
01:08:56.680 --> 01:08:59.000
Peter Smith-Kingsley. I've heard
all about you from Marge and Dickie.

848
01:08:59.080 --> 01:09:01.920
- Ditto.
- No-No glasses.

849
01:09:01.960 --> 01:09:04.680
So. where are you hiding him?
He's impossible. isn't he?

850
01:09:04.760 --> 01:09:06.800
Is he really not here?

851
01:09:06.880 --> 01:09:10.400
Marge. you know Dickie has
"l hate opera" tattooed on his chest.

852
01:09:10.440 --> 01:09:13.360
- I thought you were going to Venice.
- Yes. what happened with that?

853
01:09:13.440 --> 01:09:15.280
I heard you were
desperate to come.

854
01:09:15.360 --> 01:09:17.280
I was rather looking forward
to rowing you around.

855
01:09:17.320 --> 01:09:20.880
- I am. I really am.

856
01:09:20.960 --> 01:09:24.040
I've been traveling. and I just can't
seem to get that far north.

857
01:09:24.120 --> 01:09:25.920
Well. you should hurry.
before we sink.

858
01:09:25.960 --> 01:09:28.960
Look. let me give you
the telephone number.

859
01:09:29.000 --> 01:09:31.760
There. Oh. look.
There's Meredith.

860
01:09:31.840 --> 01:09:34.960
Meredith. What's her name.
Marge? The textile people.

861
01:09:35.040 --> 01:09:38.360
Um. come on. Some of us
spent Christmas at her house.

862
01:09:38.440 --> 01:09:42.040
I don't know her.

863
01:09:42.120 --> 01:09:45.760
He hasn't called.
He's hardly written.

864
01:09:45.800 --> 01:09:47.840
Just these cryptic
notes. you know?

865
01:09:47.920 --> 01:09:49.880
- You don't just dump people.

866
01:09:49.960 --> 01:09:53.440
Look. will we see you later.
Or are you with people?

867
01:09:53.480 --> 01:09:56.360
- Uh. I can't later.
- Well. how about tomorrow?

868
01:09:56.440 --> 01:09:58.280
Yes. uh.
maybe in the morning?

869
01:09:58.360 --> 01:10:01.880
Do you know Cafe Dinelli
at the Piazza di Spagna?

870
01:10:01.960 --> 01:10:05.280
- I know the Piazza. What time?
- 1 0:30?

871
01:10:05.360 --> 01:10:07.520
- We'll be there.
- Okay.

872
01:10:07.560 --> 01:10:09.520
So I'll see you
in the morning. Marge?

873
01:10:09.600 --> 01:10:12.520
10.:30?
Very nice to meet you.

874
01:10:12.600 --> 01:10:14.560
And you.

875
01:10:17.320 --> 01:10:19.120
Come on.

876
01:10:19.200 --> 01:10:22.960
Come on.
Let's go back in.

877
01:10:28.640 --> 01:10:31.600
I don't understand why
Tom's still in Rome.

878
01:10:31.680 --> 01:10:35.760
- Let's go.
- I thought you were enjoying yourself.

879
01:10:35.840 --> 01:10:38.040
Let's take a carrozza
and look at the moon.

880
01:10:38.120 --> 01:10:39.960
Are you crazy?
It's freezing out there.

881
01:10:40.040 --> 01:10:42.720
Come on. I need to talk to you.
Just the two of us.

882
01:10:42.800 --> 01:10:44.800
Okay.

883
01:10:48.440 --> 01:10:50.840
Don't worry. please.

884
01:10:50.920 --> 01:10:53.640
Don't worry.

885
01:10:53.720 --> 01:10:57.640
You're such a pal
to understand. I--

886
01:10:57.720 --> 01:10:59.760
It's like Marge is here
right now. I look at you.

887
01:10:59.840 --> 01:11:01.840
and I see her face.

888
01:11:01.920 --> 01:11:04.560
And I can't-- No matter
what I'm feeling towards you--

889
01:11:04.640 --> 01:11:09.800
No. I absolutely...
understand. Ofc--

890
01:11:09.840 --> 01:11:13.200
Otherwise. you'd be
fighting me off.

891
01:11:13.280 --> 01:11:15.160
Beating you away.

892
01:11:52.240 --> 01:11:55.360
But will you meet me
tomorrow?

893
01:11:55.400 --> 01:11:58.520
Just to say good-bye properly.
you know. in the daylight.

894
01:11:58.600 --> 01:12:00.640
so it's not just this.

895
01:12:00.720 --> 01:12:03.360
Of course. Meredith. I'm sorry.
Of course I'll meet you.

896
01:12:03.440 --> 01:12:08.480
You should always
save pain for daylight.

897
01:12:08.520 --> 01:12:11.680
Why don't we have coffee
in the morning at Dinelli's?

898
01:12:11.760 --> 01:12:13.840
Uh. by the Spanish Steps.

899
01:12:13.920 --> 01:12:15.680
Exactly. 1 0:30?

900
01:12:18.280 --> 01:12:20.800
- 1 0:1 5.
- Okay.

901
01:12:20.840 --> 01:12:22.920
Okay.

902
01:13:12.040 --> 01:13:14.280
- Grazie.
- Peter?

903
01:13:14.360 --> 01:13:17.720
Hello.
It's Meredith Logue.

904
01:13:17.800 --> 01:13:20.360
Of course it is.
Meredith. hello. Sorry.

905
01:13:20.440 --> 01:13:23.360
- I was half asleep. How are you?
- How are you?

906
01:13:23.440 --> 01:13:25.720
This is Marge Sherwood.
Meredith Logue.

907
01:13:25.760 --> 01:13:28.680
How do you do?

908
01:13:28.760 --> 01:13:31.960
Do join us. won't you?
We're just waiting for a friend.

909
01:13:32.000 --> 01:13:34.640
I-- I won't. actually.
I think there's--

910
01:13:34.720 --> 01:13:37.200
- Did we see you at the opera last night?
- Uh--

911
01:13:37.280 --> 01:13:39.880
Are you waiting for Dickie?

912
01:13:39.960 --> 01:13:43.920
Dickie? Do you-- Do you--
Do you know Dickie?

913
01:13:44.000 --> 01:13:47.000
You were at the opera.
Oh. that explains-- Yes. I was there.

914
01:13:47.080 --> 01:13:50.480
I was there with Dickie.

915
01:13:51.520 --> 01:13:54.160
I knew it.

916
01:13:54.240 --> 01:13:56.360
I told you.

917
01:13:58.360 --> 01:14:02.680
Marge. I don't know you.
so I've got no right to--

918
01:14:02.760 --> 01:14:05.840
Dickie loves you.
He's-- Well--

919
01:14:05.920 --> 01:14:08.920
I think you'll find
he's on his way home to you.

920
01:14:09.000 --> 01:14:12.880
Well. how-how-how
would you know that?

921
01:14:14.080 --> 01:14:16.520
He... told me everything.

922
01:14:16.600 --> 01:14:21.320
No. I was supposed to meet him
1 5 minutes ago. so. uh.

923
01:14:21.400 --> 01:14:23.720
I'm gonna go now.
I think.

924
01:14:25.920 --> 01:14:27.920
God. unless he meant us
to meet.

925
01:14:28.000 --> 01:14:30.080
That'd be a little cruel.
wouldn't it?

926
01:14:30.160 --> 01:14:32.480
No. no. we're
meeting another friend.

927
01:14:32.520 --> 01:14:35.240
- Tom Ripley.
- Do you know Tom Ripley?

928
01:14:35.320 --> 01:14:39.960
No. no. I've heard about him.
of course. but I didn't meet him. no.

929
01:14:40.000 --> 01:14:42.400
- Not for me. No. grazie.

930
01:14:47.520 --> 01:14:50.320
Hope I didn't
complicate matters.

931
01:14:50.400 --> 01:14:55.520
God. nothing. nothing...
untoward happened.

932
01:14:55.560 --> 01:14:59.640
No. there is nothing to prevent you
from welcoming him back.

933
01:14:59.680 --> 01:15:01.560
from marrying him.

934
01:15:05.920 --> 01:15:08.520
Good-bye.
I'm happy to put a face to a name.

935
01:15:08.600 --> 01:15:11.000
Good-bye. Peter.
Please. don't get up.

936
01:15:30.680 --> 01:15:33.680
Now I don't know what to
think. Do you think he's coming back?

937
01:15:35.200 --> 01:15:38.480
Sorry. Sorry.
Had to renew my papers.

938
01:15:38.560 --> 01:15:40.800
Never one stamp when they
can make you line up for three.

939
01:15:40.840 --> 01:15:42.880
- Have you been waiting long?
- Not at all.

940
01:15:42.960 --> 01:15:45.560
- Morning. Tom.
- Hi. Sorry.

941
01:15:45.640 --> 01:15:47.520
You okay? You look like
you've seen a ghost.

942
01:15:47.560 --> 01:15:50.160
Dickie was at the opera
last night.

943
01:15:50.240 --> 01:15:53.440
I don't believe that. Uh--
Wild horses couldn't drag Dickie--

944
01:15:53.480 --> 01:15:55.680
Well. he was there
with someone. you know.

945
01:15:55.760 --> 01:15:58.160
so I suppose she must
have dragged him.

946
01:15:58.240 --> 01:16:00.960
It's not fair.

947
01:16:01.000 --> 01:16:05.000
I think I'm going back to Mongi.
I think Dickie's coming home.

948
01:16:05.080 --> 01:16:07.600
Really? l-- Well.
that's just swell.

949
01:16:07.680 --> 01:16:10.200
No. you know. you're
way ahead of me. Great.

950
01:16:10.280 --> 01:16:12.160
That was rather moving
when I heard-- I'm sorry.

951
01:16:12.240 --> 01:16:14.560
Meredith is the American girl
I saw at the opera last night.

952
01:16:14.600 --> 01:16:18.520
- She's been seeing something of Dickie.
- Oh. my God.

953
01:16:18.600 --> 01:16:21.920
But the point is.
Dickie-- and we all know this.

954
01:16:22.000 --> 01:16:25.520
Dickie loves Marge.
And he misses her.

955
01:16:25.600 --> 01:16:28.240
I feel guilty.
Marge doesn't understand this.

956
01:16:28.320 --> 01:16:31.040
but whenever Dickie does
something. I feel guilty.

957
01:16:31.120 --> 01:16:33.320
As if that makes sense.

958
01:17:53.320 --> 01:17:55.200
Dickie.

959
01:17:56.800 --> 01:17:59.080
- Dickie. come on. It's me.

960
01:18:01.440 --> 01:18:03.280
It's Freddie.
Let me in.

961
01:18:06.200 --> 01:18:08.040
Dickie.

962
01:18:13.120 --> 01:18:15.800
Hello. Freddie.
It's Tom.

963
01:18:16.840 --> 01:18:19.680
Um. where's Dickie?

964
01:18:19.720 --> 01:18:21.600
How are you?

965
01:18:21.640 --> 01:18:24.600
I'm good. Uh. yes. thank you.
He's gone. He went to dinner.

966
01:18:24.640 --> 01:18:28.840
- He's at Otello's. You know Otello's?
- No. no. no.

967
01:18:28.920 --> 01:18:31.600
I-l don't think he's
at dinner at 6:30 P.M.

968
01:18:31.680 --> 01:18:34.840
If you said he was still at lunch.
maybe I'd believe you.

969
01:18:34.880 --> 01:18:38.360
You know?
Incredible.

970
01:18:38.400 --> 01:18:42.200
I mean. the guy just. you know.
disappeared off the face of the earth.

971
01:18:44.280 --> 01:18:46.120
I guess.

972
01:18:47.200 --> 01:18:50.160
The landlady.
as far as I could tell--

973
01:18:50.240 --> 01:18:53.880
The landlady said
he was here right now.

974
01:18:53.920 --> 01:18:56.080
Search the place.

975
01:18:56.160 --> 01:18:59.400
I-l just don't-- I don't know why you'd
imagine that Dickie would hide from you.

976
01:18:59.480 --> 01:19:01.320
Because he's been
hiding from me.

977
01:19:03.400 --> 01:19:07.080
- What happened at Christmas?
- What about Christmas?

978
01:19:07.160 --> 01:19:10.160
He was supposed to come skiing.
I didn't get a cable...

979
01:19:10.240 --> 01:19:12.360
or a call or a little note
or a--

980
01:19:12.440 --> 01:19:16.760
- Frankly. a fart.

981
01:19:16.840 --> 01:19:19.000
Well. he's been very involved
with his music.

982
01:19:19.080 --> 01:19:23.120
Um. I think his theory... is...

983
01:19:23.200 --> 01:19:27.600
that you have to go into a cocoon.
uh. before you can be a butterfly.

984
01:19:27.680 --> 01:19:30.120
Which is horseshit.

985
01:19:30.200 --> 01:19:33.520
You hear him play this thing?
Well. he can't.

986
01:19:36.280 --> 01:19:38.280
How did you find him?

987
01:19:38.360 --> 01:19:41.240
It's such an out-of-the-way apartment.
Can I fix you a drink?

988
01:19:41.280 --> 01:19:44.160
No. thanks.
At the American Express.

989
01:19:47.440 --> 01:19:49.760
Some kid.

990
01:19:55.040 --> 01:19:57.880
Are you living here?

991
01:19:57.920 --> 01:20:00.920
No. no. I'm staying here
for a few days.

992
01:20:03.480 --> 01:20:06.040
- But--

993
01:20:06.080 --> 01:20:09.640
It's a new piano.
Probably shouldn't--

994
01:20:14.000 --> 01:20:16.480
- Probably shouldn't--

995
01:20:19.320 --> 01:20:22.920
Did this place come furnished?

996
01:20:23.000 --> 01:20:26.040
It doesn't
Look like Dickie's. uh--

997
01:20:26.120 --> 01:20:29.080
It's really horrible.
isn't it?

998
01:20:30.600 --> 01:20:33.960
It's so. uh. bourgeois.

999
01:20:43.080 --> 01:20:45.200
Oh. that's a. uh--
You should-- Watch that.

1000
01:20:45.280 --> 01:20:48.280
Excuse--
Excuse me.

1001
01:20:48.320 --> 01:20:50.200
Excuse me.

1002
01:20:53.080 --> 01:20:57.560
In fact. the only thing that looks
like Dickie... is you.

1003
01:20:57.600 --> 01:20:59.560
- Hardly.
- Hmm.

1004
01:21:01.440 --> 01:21:04.040
Have you done something
to your hair?

1005
01:21:04.120 --> 01:21:06.040
Is there something
you'd like to say. Freddie?

1006
01:21:06.120 --> 01:21:08.440
- What?
- You have something you'd like to say?

1007
01:21:08.480 --> 01:21:10.760
I think I'm saying it.

1008
01:21:12.160 --> 01:21:15.160
Something's going on.

1009
01:21:15.240 --> 01:21:17.960
Either he's converted
to Christianity.

1010
01:21:19.120 --> 01:21:20.960
or there's something else.

1011
01:21:22.360 --> 01:21:24.400
Well. I would suggest you
ask Dickie that yourself.

1012
01:21:24.480 --> 01:21:27.240
Otello's is on della Croce
just off the Corso.

1013
01:21:27.320 --> 01:21:30.640
Is it on della Croce
just off the Corso?

1014
01:21:32.640 --> 01:21:36.720
Sure. You're
a quick study. aren't you?

1015
01:21:36.800 --> 01:21:38.640
Last time you didn't know
you ass from your elbow.

1016
01:21:38.720 --> 01:21:41.040
Now you're giving me directions.

1017
01:21:41.120 --> 01:21:44.720
That's not fair. You probably
do know your ass from your elbow.

1018
01:21:47.520 --> 01:21:49.360
I'll see you.

1019
01:22:01.000 --> 01:22:03.480
No Dickie Greenleaf. Thomas Ripley.

1020
01:22:03.560 --> 01:22:06.840
Si.

1021
01:22:11.840 --> 01:22:13.720
Ciao. Dickie.

1022
01:22:18.040 --> 01:22:20.400
Dickie doesn't
play the piano.

1023
01:22:21.880 --> 01:22:23.720
Tommy.

1024
01:22:23.800 --> 01:22:25.640
Tommy!

1025
01:22:25.720 --> 01:22:27.560
Tommy!

1026
01:23:04.520 --> 01:23:07.200
Oh!
You're making me laugh.

1027
01:23:07.280 --> 01:23:10.920
No. You're just so drunk.
Oh. You're just--

1028
01:23:11.000 --> 01:23:14.200
What can you do. eh?
You should see my other friends.

1029
01:23:14.240 --> 01:23:16.560
- What can you do?

1030
01:23:16.640 --> 01:23:19.720
Yes.
Such a pig.

1031
01:23:23.080 --> 01:23:28.120
Hey. if I'm drunk.
think what her husband's saying.

1032
01:24:13.600 --> 01:24:15.880
- Lapolizia.
- Dickie Greenleaf?

1033
01:24:15.960 --> 01:24:18.840
- Yes.
- Inspector Roverini.

1034
01:24:18.920 --> 01:24:20.840
- Can we come in?
- Please.

1035
01:24:28.280 --> 01:24:30.480
It's a terrible shock.
huh?

1036
01:24:30.560 --> 01:24:34.120
W-What time did Signor Miles
leave yesterday?

1037
01:24:34.200 --> 01:24:38.040
Oh. um. I can't be certain
exactly. I--

1038
01:24:38.120 --> 01:24:39.960
8:00. 9:00.

1039
01:24:42.720 --> 01:24:46.960
We'd both taken on. uh.
far too many drinks.

1040
01:24:47.000 --> 01:24:51.400
But it was dark. It was certainly dark
when l-- when I walked him to his car.

1041
01:24:51.480 --> 01:24:54.320
So he drove away.
and. uh. you did what?

1042
01:24:54.360 --> 01:24:57.320
- I went to bed.

1043
01:24:57.400 --> 01:25:01.880
Freddie's a big man. but I'm in trouble
after a couple of drinks.

1044
01:25:01.960 --> 01:25:05.200
I've been suffering all--

1045
01:25:05.240 --> 01:25:07.240
Who found him?

1046
01:25:07.320 --> 01:25:09.800
You understand. I must ask you...

1047
01:25:09.880 --> 01:25:12.320
to stay in Rome.
Signor Greenleaf.

1048
01:25:12.400 --> 01:25:15.600
Yes. if it's gonna help.
certainly.

1049
01:25:15.640 --> 01:25:19.280
So. the doctor. he has to make
the. um--

1050
01:25:22.640 --> 01:25:25.720
- Postmortem.
- Yeah. exactly.

1051
01:25:25.800 --> 01:25:28.360
But. you know.
his first conclusion...

1052
01:25:28.440 --> 01:25:33.280
was that Signor Miles was killed
not later than 7:00 yesterday evening.

1053
01:25:33.360 --> 01:25:36.600
Well. he certainly wasn't dead
when he drove away in his car.

1054
01:25:38.640 --> 01:25:40.480
No.

1055
01:26:04.760 --> 01:26:07.160
It's okay.

1056
01:26:07.240 --> 01:26:09.520
- Okay?
- Si. si.

1057
01:26:19.480 --> 01:26:22.960
- Did he kill Freddie?
- Marge. When did you get here?

1058
01:26:23.000 --> 01:26:25.520
Tell me the truth.
Did he kill Freddie?

1059
01:26:25.600 --> 01:26:29.000
I'd swear he didn't.
Of course he didn't.

1060
01:26:29.080 --> 01:26:33.120
I tried again.
Waiting here. watching for him.

1061
01:26:33.200 --> 01:26:36.640
Instead. it's you.
Whenever I look for Dickie. I find you.

1062
01:26:38.480 --> 01:26:41.320
What happened to your face?

1063
01:26:41.400 --> 01:26:43.280
Dickie--
Dickie did it.

1064
01:26:43.320 --> 01:26:45.480
- Dickie?
- My face. There was an argument.

1065
01:26:45.560 --> 01:26:48.120
I-- I said some things
I shouldn't have said and l--

1066
01:26:48.200 --> 01:26:51.680
About you. About the appalling way
he's treating you. all of us.

1067
01:26:51.760 --> 01:26:53.960
And the next thing I know.
he's launched himself at me.

1068
01:26:54.040 --> 01:26:56.080
- Are you getting on?
- What?

1069
01:26:56.120 --> 01:26:58.200
Get on.
I'll take you to him.

1070
01:27:40.880 --> 01:27:43.000
- Where does he live?
- We passed it a few blocks back.

1071
01:27:43.080 --> 01:27:45.400
It's where the police were.
The Palazzo Gioia.

1072
01:27:47.320 --> 01:27:50.200
Look. they don't even know I'm in Rome.
and I'm not gonna incriminate Dickie.

1073
01:27:50.240 --> 01:27:52.200
Well. perhaps
I shouldn't go either.

1074
01:27:52.280 --> 01:27:55.760
No. Well. go if you want to. but just
don't talk to the police about my face.

1075
01:27:55.800 --> 01:27:59.040
If they know he hit me and his temper.
then he could've hit Freddie.

1076
01:27:59.120 --> 01:28:01.000
I'll catch up
with you later.

1077
01:28:18.480 --> 01:28:21.320
Signor Greenleaf!

1078
01:28:21.400 --> 01:28:23.880
It's Signor Greenleaf!
Presto. presto!

1079
01:28:29.120 --> 01:28:31.240
Open the door!

1080
01:28:31.320 --> 01:28:33.600
Open up!

1081
01:28:33.680 --> 01:28:35.840
- I live here!

1082
01:28:36.960 --> 01:28:38.840
Mr. Greenleaf!

1083
01:28:40.120 --> 01:28:42.240
Can we go up?
Do you mind?

1084
01:28:42.320 --> 01:28:44.800
Of course.
What happened to your face?

1085
01:28:44.880 --> 01:28:48.400
My scooter. I fell off
getting chased by photographers.

1086
01:28:48.480 --> 01:28:52.360
The telephone. the press.
I've been-- I'm feeling hounded.

1087
01:28:52.440 --> 01:28:54.480
Do you think you could
not give out my address?

1088
01:28:54.520 --> 01:28:58.960
Never. We've had many requests.
and we say no. even to your fiancée.

1089
01:28:59.040 --> 01:29:00.920
I really don't want
to see anybody.

1090
01:29:00.960 --> 01:29:03.640
- Even your fiancée?
- Even her.

1091
01:29:06.600 --> 01:29:09.680
- What about Thomas Ripley?
- What about Tom Ripley?

1092
01:29:11.600 --> 01:29:13.520
You and Signor Ripley went to San Remo.
Is that right?

1093
01:29:13.560 --> 01:29:16.560
Yes. we-- We went to San Remo.
That was months ago.

1094
01:29:16.640 --> 01:29:18.720
November. I thought.
Was it?

1095
01:29:18.800 --> 01:29:22.200
- Did you speak to Tom?
- November 7 is my information.

1096
01:29:22.280 --> 01:29:24.920
I don't remember
the exact date.

1097
01:29:24.960 --> 01:29:29.240
- When did you last see Signor Ripley?
- A few days ago.

1098
01:29:29.280 --> 01:29:32.720
- Does he stay with you here?
- No.

1099
01:29:32.800 --> 01:29:35.080
No.

1100
01:29:36.400 --> 01:29:39.240
Here is a pattern.
Two days ago.

1101
01:29:39.320 --> 01:29:42.160
Freddie Miles is dead.
hmm?

1102
01:29:43.360 --> 01:29:45.720
He leaves your apartment.

1103
01:29:46.760 --> 01:29:49.400
and he's murdered.

1104
01:29:49.480 --> 01:29:54.400
Yesterday. a little boat
is found in San Remo full of rocks.

1105
01:29:54.480 --> 01:29:59.160
And the owner tells the police
it was stolen on November7.

1106
01:29:59.200 --> 01:30:01.600
We look at hotel records...

1107
01:30:01.680 --> 01:30:04.360
and we see...

1108
01:30:04.440 --> 01:30:07.480
Dickie Greenleaf
is staying in San Remo.

1109
01:30:07.560 --> 01:30:11.160
And then our boatman remembers
two Americans taking a boat.

1110
01:30:11.240 --> 01:30:13.920
That is not a pattern.
That's a coincidence.

1111
01:30:14.000 --> 01:30:15.880
There must be 50 hotels
in San Remo.

1112
01:30:15.960 --> 01:30:18.680
There were probably a hundred people
renting a boat that day.

1113
01:30:18.720 --> 01:30:21.120
Thirty-one people.

1114
01:30:21.200 --> 01:30:23.120
Thirty-one people.

1115
01:30:24.200 --> 01:30:26.040
Thirty-one. yeah.

1116
01:30:28.200 --> 01:30:30.680
- Marge Sherwood.
- That is Miss Sherwood now.

1117
01:30:39.080 --> 01:30:41.040
Let her in.

1118
01:30:41.080 --> 01:30:43.640
Let her in.
What's the difference? Let her in.

1119
01:30:46.000 --> 01:30:49.280
No! Actually--
Actually. no.

1120
01:30:49.360 --> 01:30:52.120
I would-- I would
really appreciate it...

1121
01:30:52.200 --> 01:30:54.960
if you would ask Miss Sherwood
to come back later.

1122
01:30:59.320 --> 01:31:02.040
Thank you.

1123
01:31:02.120 --> 01:31:05.560
May I ask you--

1124
01:31:05.640 --> 01:31:09.040
Why would you speak to your friend
and not your fiancée?

1125
01:31:09.120 --> 01:31:12.320
Well. l--
I think I just said.

1126
01:31:12.400 --> 01:31:15.600
Um. Mr. Ripley was
handling some business for me.

1127
01:31:15.640 --> 01:31:18.160
Nor does Mr. Ripley
want to marry me...

1128
01:31:18.240 --> 01:31:22.120
and ask me every single day
if I'll marry him and when.

1129
01:31:23.240 --> 01:31:25.160
Do you keep a photograph
Of Signor Ripley?

1130
01:31:25.240 --> 01:31:28.920
I'm not in the habit of carrying
around photographs of my male friends.

1131
01:31:30.520 --> 01:31:32.360
Now I think I've upset you.

1132
01:31:32.440 --> 01:31:35.440
Sorry. My English.
perhaps. is coarse.

1133
01:31:35.480 --> 01:31:37.880
It is a little coarse.
yes.

1134
01:31:41.240 --> 01:31:43.080
I'm sorry.

1135
01:31:43.160 --> 01:31:47.920
But you-- No one has seen
Signor Ripley since San Remo.

1136
01:31:48.000 --> 01:31:49.880
- I have.
- You have. yes.

1137
01:31:49.920 --> 01:31:52.560
And so has Miss Sherwood.
Ask her. And. um.

1138
01:31:52.600 --> 01:31:57.520
if I can remember the name
of the hotel he was staying at--

1139
01:31:57.600 --> 01:32:00.520
Um. the Goldoni.
Tom was staying at the Goldoni.

1140
01:32:00.600 --> 01:32:03.840
Goldoni. The Goldoni.
Good. good. but--

1141
01:32:03.920 --> 01:32:06.360
Yes. you are right.

1142
01:32:06.440 --> 01:32:08.600
You are right.
A coincidence.

1143
01:32:10.600 --> 01:32:14.040
I look forward
to our next meeting.

1144
01:32:14.120 --> 01:32:16.040
Hmm? When I will be
more careful with my English.

1145
01:32:16.120 --> 01:32:20.200
Ah. I have a witness
who thinks they saw two men...

1146
01:32:20.280 --> 01:32:22.120
getting into Mr. Miles' car.

1147
01:32:22.200 --> 01:32:25.920
And she wants to identify you
in a confronto.

1148
01:32:26.000 --> 01:32:28.400
Lineup. Tomorrow. then?

1149
01:32:29.840 --> 01:32:31.680
Uh. tomorrow.

1150
01:32:39.000 --> 01:32:40.840
- Buon giorno. Miss Sherwood.
- Buon giorno.

1151
01:32:40.920 --> 01:32:44.880
He's in. but I really don't think
he wants to meet anybody.

1152
01:33:01.560 --> 01:33:03.440
Dick?

1153
01:33:06.760 --> 01:33:08.840
Dickie?

1154
01:33:10.320 --> 01:33:12.160
I know you can hear me.

1155
01:33:20.640 --> 01:33:23.800
I was gonna say that I would count to
three. and if you didn't open the door--

1156
01:33:23.880 --> 01:33:27.960
But I won't count anymore.

1157
01:33:28.040 --> 01:33:29.960
On you.

1158
01:33:31.920 --> 01:33:35.280
I won't count on you
anymore.

1159
01:33:38.600 --> 01:33:43.320
Whatever it is you've done
or haven't done.

1160
01:33:43.360 --> 01:33:45.760
you've broken my heart.

1161
01:33:47.920 --> 01:33:50.240
That's one thing
I know you're guilty of.

1162
01:33:57.520 --> 01:33:59.840
And I don't know why.

1163
01:34:02.240 --> 01:34:05.520
I don't know why.
I just don't know why.

1164
01:34:14.960 --> 01:34:17.080
My dear Tom.

1165
01:34:17.160 --> 01:34:20.560
I'm getting out of this.

1166
01:34:20.600 --> 01:34:24.000
Freddie's death. Silvana.

1167
01:34:24.080 --> 01:34:28.120
I've thought about going to the police.
but I can't do it.

1168
01:34:28.160 --> 01:34:30.440
I can't face it.

1169
01:34:30.520 --> 01:34:32.120
I can't face anything anymore.

1170
01:34:32.120 --> 01:34:33.160
I can't face anything anymore.

1171
01:34:33.240 --> 01:34:35.880
I wish I could give you
the life I took for granted.

1172
01:34:38.840 --> 01:34:41.280
You've always understood
what's at the heart of me. Tom.

1173
01:34:41.360 --> 01:34:44.600
Marge never could.

1174
01:34:44.640 --> 01:34:47.920
I suppose that's why
I'm writing this to you.

1175
01:34:47.960 --> 01:34:50.480
the brother I never had.

1176
01:34:50.560 --> 01:34:53.200
The only true friend
I ever had.

1177
01:34:58.640 --> 01:35:00.480
In all kinds of ways.

1178
01:35:00.560 --> 01:35:04.680
you're much more like the son
my father wanted.

1179
01:35:04.760 --> 01:35:07.840
I realize you can
change the people.

1180
01:35:07.920 --> 01:35:10.320
change thescenery.

1181
01:35:10.360 --> 01:35:12.480
but you can't change
your own rotten self.

1182
01:35:15.160 --> 01:35:17.800
Now I can't think what to do
or where to go.

1183
01:35:19.800 --> 01:35:24.200
I'm haunted by everything
I've done and can't undo.

1184
01:35:25.720 --> 01:35:27.600
I'm sorry.

1185
01:35:29.600 --> 01:35:32.840
I've made a mess of being
Dickie Greenleaf. haven't I?

1186
01:36:34.560 --> 01:36:37.440
Tom!

1187
01:36:39.520 --> 01:36:42.680
I'll see you over there!

1188
01:36:50.720 --> 01:36:52.920
I'm so sorry to put you
through this. Peter.

1189
01:36:53.000 --> 01:36:56.440
I just can't face going to the police
by myself when my Italian's so rotten.

1190
01:36:56.520 --> 01:36:58.440
Don't be so daft.
It's fine.

1191
01:36:58.520 --> 01:37:01.040
I'm delighted you finally
made it to Venice.

1192
01:37:01.120 --> 01:37:03.640
I'm delighted. contrary to rumor.
that you're still in one piece.

1193
01:37:03.720 --> 01:37:05.640
- What rumor?
- Oh. you know.

1194
01:37:05.720 --> 01:37:09.000
That Dickie murdered you
and is traveling under your passport.

1195
01:37:09.080 --> 01:37:11.080
I know. It's ridiculous.

1196
01:37:25.320 --> 01:37:27.160
Welcome to Venice.

1197
01:37:27.240 --> 01:37:30.160
God. this place reeks. doesn't it?
Can you smell it?

1198
01:37:30.200 --> 01:37:33.920
Anyway. I've got to
the bottom of the delay. finally.

1199
01:37:34.000 --> 01:37:36.800
We're waiting
for someone from Rome.

1200
01:37:36.880 --> 01:37:39.120
What do you mean?
They've sent for someone from Rome?

1201
01:37:39.160 --> 01:37:42.160
- Well. yes. That's good. isn't it?
- No. I thought...

1202
01:37:42.240 --> 01:37:45.480
that didn't happen in Italy.
that each region is separate.

1203
01:37:45.560 --> 01:37:47.880
I was sure that--
I've read that--

1204
01:37:47.960 --> 01:37:50.680
You've read the papers.
You know what a big deal it's been.

1205
01:37:50.760 --> 01:37:53.680
- American tourist murdered.
- Actually. can we not do this now?

1206
01:37:53.760 --> 01:37:57.680
- The stench really is--

1207
01:38:14.240 --> 01:38:18.680
He's taken over the case. 'cause they're
annoyed that the previous chap...

1208
01:38:18.760 --> 01:38:21.520
let Dickie disappear
when he was. um.

1209
01:38:21.560 --> 01:38:23.480
the only suspect
in Freddie's murder.

1210
01:38:26.400 --> 01:38:29.560
In Rome.
about three weeks ago.

1211
01:38:29.600 --> 01:38:31.480
I knew that one.

1212
01:38:31.520 --> 01:38:35.440
Um--

1213
01:38:38.400 --> 01:38:43.040
Are you a homosexual?
Interesting non sequitur.

1214
01:38:43.120 --> 01:38:45.040
No.

1215
01:38:45.120 --> 01:38:48.240
- No.
- Oh.

1216
01:38:48.280 --> 01:38:53.000
By the way. um. officially
there are no Italian homosexuals.

1217
01:38:53.080 --> 01:38:55.480
Makes Michelangelo and
Leonardo very inconvenient.

1218
01:38:55.560 --> 01:38:57.200
Eh?

1219
01:38:57.240 --> 01:39:00.320
Tell him...
I have a fiancée.

1220
01:39:00.400 --> 01:39:02.680
And Dickie has a fiancée.

1221
01:39:02.720 --> 01:39:06.200
And that Freddie Miles
probably had a string of them.

1222
01:39:17.400 --> 01:39:21.120
Mamma mia.

1223
01:39:24.560 --> 01:39:26.680
- What did he say?
- He says "so many fiancées."

1224
01:39:31.640 --> 01:39:34.520
He's asking... if you
Killed Freddie Miles...

1225
01:39:34.560 --> 01:39:36.440
and then killed Dickie Greenleaf.

1226
01:39:36.480 --> 01:39:40.280
No! No. I did not kill Freddie Miles
and then kill Dickie Greenleaf.

1227
01:39:40.360 --> 01:39:43.440
Is he accusing me?
Ask him if he's accusing me.

1228
01:39:43.480 --> 01:39:46.160
The way it works here.
it's better to be less volatile.

1229
01:39:46.200 --> 01:39:48.280
- But it's absurd!

1230
01:40:03.160 --> 01:40:07.440
They found this
in Dickie's place in Rome.

1231
01:40:07.520 --> 01:40:10.000
- You opened this?
- Of course.

1232
01:40:25.640 --> 01:40:28.360
It's a suicide note.

1233
01:40:32.000 --> 01:40:35.720
You asked me all these questions and you
already read this suicide note?

1234
01:40:53.320 --> 01:40:55.320
I don't believe that letter.
Do you?

1235
01:40:55.400 --> 01:40:58.800
Dickie's letter.
Do you believe it?

1236
01:40:58.840 --> 01:41:01.200
I don't know
what to believe.

1237
01:41:01.240 --> 01:41:05.760
Can you imagine. though. if he did
kill Freddie. what that must be like?

1238
01:41:05.880 --> 01:41:09.560
Just to wake up every morning.
I mean. how can you?

1239
01:41:09.640 --> 01:41:12.960
Just wake up and be a person?
Drink your coffee.

1240
01:41:13.040 --> 01:41:17.280
Well. what ever you do.
however terrible. however hurtful.

1241
01:41:17.320 --> 01:41:20.520
it all makes sense.
doesn't it. in your head.

1242
01:41:20.560 --> 01:41:23.240
You never meet anybody
who thinks they're a bad person.

1243
01:41:23.280 --> 01:41:27.160
No. I know. but you're still tormented.
You must be. You've killed someone.

1244
01:41:27.240 --> 01:41:30.240
Don't you just take the past
and put it in a room in the basement.

1245
01:41:30.320 --> 01:41:32.200
and lock the door
and never go in there?

1246
01:41:32.280 --> 01:41:35.520
- That's what I do.
- God. yes.

1247
01:41:35.560 --> 01:41:40.040
But. of course. in my case.
it's probably a whole building.

1248
01:41:40.080 --> 01:41:43.000
- And then you meet someone special.

1249
01:41:43.080 --> 01:41:46.960
and all you want to do
is toss them the key.

1250
01:41:48.240 --> 01:41:50.720
Say "Open up. Step inside."

1251
01:41:53.320 --> 01:41:55.440
But you can't...

1252
01:41:55.520 --> 01:41:58.160
- because it's dark...

1253
01:41:58.240 --> 01:42:01.000
and there are demons.

1254
01:42:02.000 --> 01:42:04.360
And if anybody saw
how ugly it is--

1255
01:42:08.880 --> 01:42:10.840
Now that's the music talking.

1256
01:42:13.000 --> 01:42:16.200
It's harder to be bleak if you're
playing "Knees Up. Mother Brown."

1257
01:42:21.680 --> 01:42:24.520
I keep wanting to do that.

1258
01:42:24.600 --> 01:42:28.320
Fling...
the door open.

1259
01:42:30.600 --> 01:42:34.200
Just let the light in.
clean everything out.

1260
01:42:36.400 --> 01:42:40.240
If I could take a giant eraser
and rub out everything.

1261
01:42:40.320 --> 01:42:43.120
starting with myself--

1262
01:42:45.600 --> 01:42:48.680
The thing is. Peter. if--

1263
01:42:51.120 --> 01:42:54.600
- Hmm?
- If--

1264
01:42:56.360 --> 01:42:58.240
If--

1265
01:43:05.000 --> 01:43:07.240
No key. huh?

1266
01:43:49.840 --> 01:43:51.760
- Marge.
- Peter.

1267
01:43:54.120 --> 01:43:56.000
- So good to see you.
- Hello. Marge.

1268
01:43:56.040 --> 01:43:58.160
Tom.

1269
01:43:58.240 --> 01:44:02.120
- I see you found Peter.
- I think we sort of found each other.

1270
01:44:02.200 --> 01:44:05.760
- Where's Dickie's father?
- He's not coming till the morning.

1271
01:44:05.840 --> 01:44:09.240
Evidently his stomach. I don't think
the food here is agreeing with him.

1272
01:44:09.320 --> 01:44:11.160
Oh. I was looking forward
to seeing him.

1273
01:44:11.240 --> 01:44:13.840
Dickie hasn't killed himself.
I'm sure of that.

1274
01:44:13.920 --> 01:44:16.360
There's a private detective
on the case now.

1275
01:44:16.440 --> 01:44:18.840
A Mr. MacCarron
Dickie's father's employed.

1276
01:44:18.920 --> 01:44:22.120
- That's a terrific idea.
- He's American.

1277
01:44:22.200 --> 01:44:25.400
He's already discovered
that Dickie cashed checks for $1 .000...

1278
01:44:25.480 --> 01:44:27.560
the day before
he disappeared.

1279
01:44:27.640 --> 01:44:29.480
Signora.

1280
01:44:29.560 --> 01:44:32.840
Is that what you do
before you jump into the Tiber?

1281
01:44:32.920 --> 01:44:35.400
I don't think so.

1282
01:44:39.080 --> 01:44:41.200
- Is this you?
- No. it's Tom's.

1283
01:44:41.280 --> 01:44:43.120
Splendid. eh?

1284
01:44:43.200 --> 01:44:46.400
Golly.
Who's paying for this?

1285
01:44:46.440 --> 01:44:48.360
Peter found it for me.

1286
01:44:48.400 --> 01:44:53.120
I can afford it because
it's damp and... falling down.

1287
01:44:53.160 --> 01:44:56.200
- Tom's transformed it.
- This is spectacular.

1288
01:44:56.280 --> 01:44:58.440
That's why
Tom wanted you to stay.

1289
01:44:58.520 --> 01:45:01.000
It's better than trying
to squeeze into my room.

1290
01:45:01.080 --> 01:45:03.080
And I know
How you hate hotels.

1291
01:45:03.160 --> 01:45:05.080
A hotel would have been fine.

1292
01:45:08.400 --> 01:45:12.760
We'll have to tell Mr. Greenleaf
how far his dollar stretched.

1293
01:45:16.000 --> 01:45:18.880
- What's funny?

1294
01:45:18.960 --> 01:45:22.360
I was just thinking about when
Tom first came to Mongibello.

1295
01:45:24.320 --> 01:45:27.640
- And look at you now.
- Look at me what?

1296
01:45:28.840 --> 01:45:30.760
To the manor born.

1297
01:45:44.320 --> 01:45:46.440
Mr. Greenleaf?

1298
01:45:50.160 --> 01:45:52.040
Mr. Greenleaf?

1299
01:45:52.080 --> 01:45:55.640
Tom. How are you?
You look well.

1300
01:45:55.720 --> 01:45:58.440
- Thank you. sir. I am well.
- Far cry from New York.

1301
01:45:58.480 --> 01:46:00.880
- Yes. it is.
- Marge.

1302
01:46:00.960 --> 01:46:03.880
Good morning.
Unusual weather.

1303
01:46:03.960 --> 01:46:06.720
- Very.
- And you. sir. Any better?

1304
01:46:06.760 --> 01:46:09.760
Pretty good.
Sticking with hot water.

1305
01:46:09.840 --> 01:46:12.040
- Where's Mr. MacCarron?
- San Remo.

1306
01:46:12.120 --> 01:46:14.760
The police are amateurs.

1307
01:46:14.800 --> 01:46:19.160
Well. my boy. it's come
to a pretty pass. hasn't it?

1308
01:46:19.240 --> 01:46:22.280
What is the detective
hoping to find in San Remo?

1309
01:46:22.360 --> 01:46:27.000
He's being thorough.
I'm learning about my son. Tom.

1310
01:46:27.080 --> 01:46:30.360
Now he's missing.
I'm learning a great deal about him.

1311
01:46:30.440 --> 01:46:33.400
and I hope that you can
fill in some more blanks for me.

1312
01:46:33.480 --> 01:46:36.400
Marge has been good enough
to do that about Mongibello.

1313
01:46:36.480 --> 01:46:40.120
I'll try my best. sir. Obviously.
I'll do anything to help Dickie.

1314
01:46:40.200 --> 01:46:42.560
- Good. This theory.

1315
01:46:42.640 --> 01:46:44.680
the letter
he left for you.

1316
01:46:44.760 --> 01:46:47.880
The police think that's
a clear indication...

1317
01:46:47.960 --> 01:46:51.560
he was planning on doing something.
uh. to himself.

1318
01:46:51.600 --> 01:46:54.280
I just don't believe that.

1319
01:46:54.360 --> 01:46:56.800
You don't want to. dear.

1320
01:46:59.880 --> 01:47:01.800
I'd like
to talk to Tom alone.

1321
01:47:01.880 --> 01:47:04.560
Perhaps this afternoon.
Would you mind?

1322
01:47:06.920 --> 01:47:10.760
Marge. what a man may say
to his sweetheart...

1323
01:47:10.840 --> 01:47:12.920
and what he'll admit
to another fellow--

1324
01:47:16.080 --> 01:47:18.680
Such as?

1325
01:47:22.240 --> 01:47:25.360
What a waste of lives and opportunities.

1326
01:47:25.440 --> 01:47:28.320
I'd pay that fellow a hundred dollars
right now to shut up!

1327
01:47:36.320 --> 01:47:39.560
No. Marge doesn't
know the half of it.

1328
01:47:39.600 --> 01:47:42.760
And his passport photo.

1329
01:47:42.800 --> 01:47:45.560
Did you hear? To scratch out
his own face like that?

1330
01:47:45.680 --> 01:47:47.720
Can you imagine?

1331
01:47:47.800 --> 01:47:50.920
Frame of mind
you'd have to be in?

1332
01:47:51.000 --> 01:47:54.160
"I've thought about going to the police.
but I can't face it.

1333
01:47:54.240 --> 01:47:57.640
I can't face
anything anymore."

1334
01:47:57.680 --> 01:48:00.880
I feel guilty. I feel
like I pushed him away.

1335
01:48:00.960 --> 01:48:02.920
I feel like I spoke
and he heard you.

1336
01:48:03.000 --> 01:48:05.680
Well.

1337
01:48:05.760 --> 01:48:08.240
if we all pushed him away.
what about him pushing us away?

1338
01:48:08.320 --> 01:48:10.800
You've been a great friend
to my son.

1339
01:48:10.880 --> 01:48:13.880
Everything is
someone else's fault.

1340
01:48:13.960 --> 01:48:16.320
We all want to sow
wild oats.

1341
01:48:16.400 --> 01:48:19.560
but somebody's got to--
got to--

1342
01:48:19.640 --> 01:48:22.320
What is the word?

1343
01:48:22.400 --> 01:48:25.480
You know. the moment
someone confronts him.

1344
01:48:26.800 --> 01:48:29.200
he lashes out.

1345
01:48:29.280 --> 01:48:31.720
He always has.

1346
01:48:31.800 --> 01:48:35.520
You know. people always say
that you can't choose your parents.

1347
01:48:40.080 --> 01:48:42.440
but you can't choose
your children.

1348
01:48:43.760 --> 01:48:47.200
- Dickie.

1349
01:48:47.280 --> 01:48:50.720
You can be a leech.
You can be quite boring.

1350
01:48:50.800 --> 01:48:52.640
- Stop it!
- It's boring.

1351
01:48:56.560 --> 01:48:58.800
Stop. stop. stop!

1352
01:49:00.240 --> 01:49:02.080
- Stop. stop. stop!
- Tommy. Tommy.

1353
01:49:02.160 --> 01:49:04.000
Like a little girl.

1354
01:49:04.080 --> 01:49:07.040
- Like a little girl.

1355
01:49:10.520 --> 01:49:12.400
- Coming.

1356
01:49:12.480 --> 01:49:14.760
- Sorry. I was asleep.
- Finally.

1357
01:49:14.800 --> 01:49:16.840
- I must have fallen asleep.
- Did Dickie's dad go?

1358
01:49:16.920 --> 01:49:18.800
You look ghastly. Tom.
Did you have a nightmare?

1359
01:49:18.840 --> 01:49:21.920
- He's having an early night.
- Oh. poor man.

1360
01:49:22.000 --> 01:49:24.360
You know. we were banging
on that door forever.

1361
01:49:27.800 --> 01:49:29.680
Uh-oh.

1362
01:49:29.720 --> 01:49:33.160
- I think I've broken a strap.
- Not guilty.

1363
01:49:33.240 --> 01:49:36.080
- I'll fix some drinks.

1364
01:49:36.160 --> 01:49:38.680
Ah!
You walk in Venice.

1365
01:49:40.160 --> 01:49:42.000
Are you okay?

1366
01:49:43.440 --> 01:49:45.200
I'm fine.

1367
01:49:45.280 --> 01:49:49.280
- Did you want me to stick around?
- No. it's okay.

1368
01:49:51.240 --> 01:49:53.320
I could come back.

1369
01:50:08.040 --> 01:50:10.080
Your key.

1370
01:50:13.640 --> 01:50:16.200
- Tom?

1371
01:50:16.280 --> 01:50:19.640
Marge. I'm in the bath.
I won't be long.

1372
01:50:19.720 --> 01:50:21.840
Tom. I have to speak to you.
It's urgent.

1373
01:50:25.440 --> 01:50:27.280
Coming.

1374
01:50:38.320 --> 01:50:41.480
- I found Dickie's rings.
- What?

1375
01:50:41.560 --> 01:50:43.480
You have Dickie's rings.

1376
01:50:48.080 --> 01:50:49.920
I can explain.

1377
01:50:50.000 --> 01:50:52.560
Dickie promised me he would
Never take off this ring.

1378
01:50:52.640 --> 01:50:55.560
Let me put some clothes on
and we'll talk about this.

1379
01:50:55.640 --> 01:50:57.960
- I have to tell Mr. Greenleaf.
- Marge. you're being hysterical.

1380
01:50:58.040 --> 01:51:01.360
He promised me. "l swear. I will never
take off this ring until we get--"

1381
01:51:01.440 --> 01:51:03.280
- Shut up!

1382
01:51:05.400 --> 01:51:08.720
I'm wet. Marge.
I've lost my towel.

1383
01:51:08.800 --> 01:51:11.680
And I'd really like
To put some clothes on.

1384
01:51:11.760 --> 01:51:13.680
Go and pour us both a drink.

1385
01:51:16.960 --> 01:51:18.800
Pour us a drink.

1386
01:51:50.800 --> 01:51:53.040
Marge?

1387
01:51:53.120 --> 01:51:55.280
Where are you going?

1388
01:51:55.360 --> 01:51:58.680
I wasn't snooping.
I just--

1389
01:51:58.760 --> 01:52:01.560
I was looking for a needle
and thread to mend my bra.

1390
01:52:03.480 --> 01:52:06.920
That scent you're wearing.

1391
01:52:07.000 --> 01:52:10.120
I bought that
For you.

1392
01:52:10.160 --> 01:52:12.640
The thing about Dickie--

1393
01:52:12.720 --> 01:52:14.560
So many things.

1394
01:52:16.400 --> 01:52:19.840
That day when he was late
coming back from Rome.

1395
01:52:19.920 --> 01:52:21.760
I tried to tell you this.

1396
01:52:21.840 --> 01:52:25.160
He was with another girl.
I'm not talking about Meredith. either.

1397
01:52:25.240 --> 01:52:28.360
Another girl
that we met in a bar.

1398
01:52:28.400 --> 01:52:31.360
He couldn't be faithful
For five minutes.

1399
01:52:31.440 --> 01:52:33.360
So when he makes a promise.

1400
01:52:33.440 --> 01:52:35.400
it doesn't mean what it means
when you make a promise...

1401
01:52:35.480 --> 01:52:37.960
or I make a promise.

1402
01:52:38.000 --> 01:52:41.840
He has so many realities. Dickie.
and he believes them all.

1403
01:52:41.920 --> 01:52:45.000
He lies. He lies.

1404
01:52:45.040 --> 01:52:49.280
And that's his-Half the time
he doesn't even realize he's doing it.

1405
01:52:49.360 --> 01:52:52.520
And today.

1406
01:52:52.560 --> 01:52:56.200
I really started wondering whether
he may have killed Freddie.

1407
01:52:56.280 --> 01:52:59.720
He would get so crazy
If anybody would contradict him.

1408
01:52:59.800 --> 01:53:02.400
Well. you know that.
You know that.

1409
01:53:02.480 --> 01:53:05.000
You know that.

1410
01:53:05.040 --> 01:53:07.240
And that's the irony. Marge.

1411
01:53:07.280 --> 01:53:09.160
I loved you.

1412
01:53:09.200 --> 01:53:11.080
You may as well know. Marge.
I loved you.

1413
01:53:11.120 --> 01:53:13.760
I don't know. maybe it's
grotesque of me to say this now.

1414
01:53:13.840 --> 01:53:16.520
so just... write it on apiece
of paper or something...

1415
01:53:16.600 --> 01:53:18.960
and put it in your purse
for a rainy day.

1416
01:53:19.040 --> 01:53:23.080
"Tom loves me. Tom loves me."

1417
01:53:23.160 --> 01:53:25.440
- Why do you have Dickie's rings?
- I told you.

1418
01:53:25.520 --> 01:53:28.480
- He gave them to me.
- Why? When?

1419
01:53:28.560 --> 01:53:31.440
I feel as if you haven't been listening
to anything I've been saying to you.

1420
01:53:31.520 --> 01:53:34.640
I don't believe you.
I don't believe you.

1421
01:53:34.720 --> 01:53:36.960
- It's all true.
- I don't believe...

1422
01:53:37.040 --> 01:53:41.240
a single word you've said.

1423
01:53:41.320 --> 01:53:43.920
You're shivering. Marge.
Look at you.

1424
01:53:44.000 --> 01:53:47.640
Marge. can I hold you?

1425
01:53:47.720 --> 01:53:49.600
Will you let me hold you?

1426
01:53:49.680 --> 01:53:51.640
- Marge?

1427
01:53:51.760 --> 01:53:54.680
- Peter! Thank God you're here.
- What's going on?

1428
01:53:54.760 --> 01:53:57.960
Get me out of here.
Get me out of here. Please!

1429
01:53:58.040 --> 01:54:02.680
- Tom. are you okay?

1430
01:54:02.720 --> 01:54:05.720
You try.
You try talking to her.

1431
01:54:06.760 --> 01:54:08.760
- Tom?
- I give up.

1432
01:54:08.840 --> 01:54:11.320
Tell me what's going on.
Tom!

1433
01:54:11.400 --> 01:54:13.760
- What did I ever do to her?
- Listen--

1434
01:54:13.840 --> 01:54:16.840
Have her tell you one thing
that I've ever done to her.

1435
01:54:16.920 --> 01:54:19.480
You can't be angry
with her.

1436
01:54:19.560 --> 01:54:22.400
She's confused. and she needs
someone to blame.

1437
01:54:22.440 --> 01:54:24.320
So she blames you.

1438
01:54:24.360 --> 01:54:26.840
I'll go back home
and talk to her.

1439
01:54:26.880 --> 01:54:29.280
As for you.

1440
01:54:29.360 --> 01:54:31.880
either get a safety razor
or grow a beard.

1441
01:54:44.360 --> 01:54:47.400
- Is Mr. Greenleaf here?
- Mr. Ripley?

1442
01:54:47.480 --> 01:54:50.040
- Yes.
- I'm Alvin MacCarron.

1443
01:54:52.640 --> 01:54:55.200
I don't know.
I don't know. I just know it.

1444
01:54:55.280 --> 01:54:58.080
Marge. there's female
intuition and then there are facts.

1445
01:55:00.560 --> 01:55:02.400
- Tom.
- Sir.

1446
01:55:02.480 --> 01:55:05.080
Marge. you should have waited.
I didn't--

1447
01:55:05.160 --> 01:55:07.720
Didn't Peter say I'd
come by and pick you up?

1448
01:55:08.800 --> 01:55:11.320
Marge has been telling us
about the rings.

1449
01:55:11.360 --> 01:55:13.760
Yes. I feel ridiculous
I didn't mention them yesterday.

1450
01:55:13.840 --> 01:55:16.160
I clean forgot.
Ridiculous.

1451
01:55:18.640 --> 01:55:22.760
Perhaps you didn't mention them because
there's only one conclusion to be drawn.

1452
01:55:24.760 --> 01:55:27.880
I'm going to take Marge for a walk.
Tom. Mr. MacCarron needs to talk to you.

1453
01:55:27.960 --> 01:55:30.080
There's no need. We could go
to the bar. There's no need.

1454
01:55:30.160 --> 01:55:32.280
No. no.

1455
01:55:32.320 --> 01:55:34.520
I think you should
stay here.

1456
01:55:55.480 --> 01:55:57.840
I could probably
see my room from here.

1457
01:55:57.920 --> 01:55:59.800
I can see my house.

1458
01:56:01.720 --> 01:56:05.680
When you see where you live from a
distance. it's like a dream. isn't it?

1459
01:56:05.760 --> 01:56:07.920
I don't care for B.S.

1460
01:56:08.000 --> 01:56:10.520
I don't care to hear it.
I don't care to speak it.

1461
01:56:12.640 --> 01:56:14.840
- Okay.
- Did you know that at Princeton...

1462
01:56:14.880 --> 01:56:17.120
Dickie Greenleaf
half-killed a boy?

1463
01:56:18.160 --> 01:56:20.080
At a party over some girl.

1464
01:56:20.160 --> 01:56:23.880
Kicked the kid several times
in the head. put him in the hospital.

1465
01:56:23.960 --> 01:56:27.640
Boy had a wire fixed in his jaw.
lost some hearing.

1466
01:56:27.680 --> 01:56:30.840
Why do you think Dickie's father
sent him to Europe in the first place?

1467
01:56:33.440 --> 01:56:37.480
The Rome police didn't think
to ask Mr. Greenleaf.

1468
01:56:37.560 --> 01:56:40.400
Nor did they think to check
on whether a Thomas Ripley...

1469
01:56:40.480 --> 01:56:43.520
had ever been a student
at Princeton University.

1470
01:56:43.600 --> 01:56:48.040
Oh. I turned up
a Tom Ripley...

1471
01:56:48.120 --> 01:56:52.040
who had been a piano tuner
in the music department.

1472
01:56:53.080 --> 01:56:55.080
You see. in America.

1473
01:56:55.160 --> 01:56:59.480
we are taught to check a fact
before it becomes a fact.

1474
01:56:59.560 --> 01:57:01.880
We're taught to nose around.

1475
01:57:01.920 --> 01:57:04.680
When a girl drowns herself.

1476
01:57:04.760 --> 01:57:07.040
find out if
that girl is pregnant.

1477
01:57:07.120 --> 01:57:09.920
Find out if Dickie
Had an embarrassment there.

1478
01:57:11.280 --> 01:57:14.520
Mr. Greenleaf appreciates your loyalty.
He really does.

1479
01:57:14.560 --> 01:57:17.520
Marge--
She has a hundred theories.

1480
01:57:17.600 --> 01:57:20.400
There are a few things
that she doesn't know.

1481
01:57:20.480 --> 01:57:22.360
We hope she never knows.

1482
01:57:22.440 --> 01:57:24.600
I hope she never knows.

1483
01:57:24.640 --> 01:57:27.040
Three different people...

1484
01:57:27.120 --> 01:57:30.520
saw Dickie
get into Freddie's car.

1485
01:57:30.600 --> 01:57:33.760
One man.
who will not testify...

1486
01:57:33.840 --> 01:57:36.640
because he was jumping somebody
else's wife at the time.

1487
01:57:36.720 --> 01:57:40.560
saw Dickie removing license plates
from a red sports car.

1488
01:57:40.640 --> 01:57:44.440
The police know about this man because
he happens to be a policeman.

1489
01:57:46.400 --> 01:57:49.720
I found these in the basement
of Dickie's apartment.

1490
01:57:49.800 --> 01:57:51.800
They belong to Freddie's car.

1491
01:57:51.880 --> 01:57:56.000
Mr. Greenleaf has asked me...

1492
01:57:56.080 --> 01:57:58.840
to lose these in the canal
this evening.

1493
01:58:03.840 --> 01:58:06.560
Mr. Greenleaf feels that
there was a silent promise...

1494
01:58:06.640 --> 01:58:09.680
in Dickie's letter to you
which he intends to honor.

1495
01:58:09.760 --> 01:58:12.200
He also intends to transfer
A good portion...

1496
01:58:12.280 --> 01:58:16.800
of Dickie's income from his trust
into your name.

1497
01:58:16.880 --> 01:58:18.880
He does not intend...

1498
01:58:18.960 --> 01:58:22.280
to give the Italians any
information about Dickie's past.

1499
01:58:24.160 --> 01:58:27.800
He's rather hoping that...
you will feel the same.

1500
01:58:45.120 --> 01:58:46.960
- Thank you so much. Tom.
- Sir.

1501
01:58:47.040 --> 01:58:48.880
Good-bye.

1502
01:58:53.320 --> 01:58:57.440
Marge. I feel I never should have said
those things to you the other evening.

1503
01:58:57.520 --> 01:59:01.360
I was pretty flustered.
and the rings-- And you looked so--

1504
01:59:01.440 --> 01:59:03.640
I don't know.

1505
01:59:03.680 --> 01:59:07.600
But I hope that note goes
in your purse to New York...

1506
01:59:07.680 --> 01:59:10.040
for a rainy day.

1507
01:59:11.520 --> 01:59:15.080
- What are you gonna do now. Tom?
- I don't know.

1508
01:59:15.160 --> 01:59:17.200
Peter has a concert in Athens
next month.

1509
01:59:17.280 --> 01:59:19.760
so he asked me to come along
and help out.

1510
01:59:22.240 --> 01:59:24.080
He says good-bye.

1511
01:59:24.160 --> 01:59:26.040
By the way. he was
in rehearsal so he couldn't--

1512
01:59:26.080 --> 01:59:30.120
Why do I think there's
never been a Ripley rainy day?

1513
01:59:30.200 --> 01:59:32.680
What?

1514
01:59:32.760 --> 01:59:36.320
I know it was you.
I know it was you.

1515
01:59:36.400 --> 01:59:39.120
I know it was you!
I know it was you!

1516
01:59:39.200 --> 01:59:42.680
- Marge. Marge. Please!
- I know you killed Dickie!

1517
01:59:42.760 --> 01:59:44.600
- Marge!
- I know! No!

1518
01:59:44.680 --> 01:59:48.040
I know it was you!

1519
01:59:48.120 --> 01:59:50.040
Marge.
Marge. please.

1520
01:59:50.120 --> 01:59:52.680
It's not Tom.
Really.

1521
02:00:00.920 --> 02:00:04.040
We are called gondoleri

1522
02:00:04.120 --> 02:00:07.920
But that's a vagary
It's quite honorary

1523
02:00:08.120 --> 02:00:13.160
The trade that we ply

1524
02:00:13.280 --> 02:00:15.920
Ask me what I want to change
about this moment.

1525
02:00:16.000 --> 02:00:18.360
I don't know. What do you want
to change about this moment?

1526
02:00:18.400 --> 02:00:20.040
Nothing.

1527
02:00:23.560 --> 02:00:26.240
I'm freezing. Coming down?

1528
02:00:26.320 --> 02:00:29.040
Later. I want
to catch the sunset.

1529
02:00:29.120 --> 02:00:33.200
- You're mad.
- I am.

1530
02:00:42.720 --> 02:00:44.560
Dickie?

1531
02:00:47.640 --> 02:00:49.480
Dickie?

1532
02:00:52.760 --> 02:00:54.600
Dickie!

1533
02:01:05.240 --> 02:01:07.080
Oh. my God.

1534
02:01:08.960 --> 02:01:10.840
Hello. Meredith.

1535
02:01:13.840 --> 02:01:16.080
I was looking at you.

1536
02:01:16.160 --> 02:01:19.440
Your clothes.
I wouldn't have known you.

1537
02:01:19.520 --> 02:01:22.160
Well. you spotted me.
So you get the reward.

1538
02:01:23.760 --> 02:01:26.320
- What?
-Just kidding.

1539
02:01:26.400 --> 02:01:30.200
- Are you alone?
- Oh.

1540
02:01:30.240 --> 02:01:33.160
Hardly.
Couldn't be less alone.

1541
02:01:33.240 --> 02:01:35.800
- Aunt Joan.
- And "co."

1542
02:01:38.800 --> 02:01:40.680
A lot of "co."

1543
02:01:41.760 --> 02:01:44.760
Oh. God.

1544
02:01:44.840 --> 02:01:47.800
You know. seeing you again. l--

1545
02:01:49.800 --> 02:01:52.960
I've thought about you...

1546
02:01:53.000 --> 02:01:54.880
so much.

1547
02:01:54.920 --> 02:01:56.800
And I've thought about you.

1548
02:01:58.760 --> 02:02:02.080
Yeah. well. when I've thought about you.
I was mostly hating you.

1549
02:02:08.400 --> 02:02:10.280
Where have you been hiding?

1550
02:02:10.360 --> 02:02:13.720
I haven't been hiding.

1551
02:02:13.800 --> 02:02:16.040
I've been in police custody.

1552
02:02:17.320 --> 02:02:20.160
They've been trying to
flush out Freddie's killer.

1553
02:02:20.200 --> 02:02:23.280
- You're kidding.
- They're giving me this vacation.

1554
02:02:23.360 --> 02:02:25.560
which is why
the getup.

1555
02:02:25.600 --> 02:02:27.680
Which is why
you haven't heard from me.

1556
02:02:27.760 --> 02:02:29.960
You know. the whole world
thinks you killed Freddie.

1557
02:02:30.040 --> 02:02:33.000
- Oh! It's terrible.
- I know.

1558
02:02:33.080 --> 02:02:35.680
Listen. I can't
talk now. Um. later?

1559
02:02:39.480 --> 02:02:42.720
Later? Later?

1560
02:02:52.520 --> 02:02:54.400
So--

1561
02:02:59.440 --> 02:03:02.000
Are you traveling
under "R"?

1562
02:03:02.080 --> 02:03:05.000
You know what? I am.

1563
02:03:07.960 --> 02:03:12.160
Dickie. are you with Peter
Smith-Kingsley? I bet you are.

1564
02:03:12.200 --> 02:03:14.720
My aunt
thought she saw him.

1565
02:03:14.800 --> 02:03:16.840
Peter Smith-Kingsley?
No. l--

1566
02:03:16.920 --> 02:03:20.400
I haven't seen him
in months.

1567
02:03:20.480 --> 02:03:22.320
No. I'm alone.

1568
02:03:41.280 --> 02:03:43.160
Hi.

1569
02:03:45.760 --> 02:03:48.160
- How was it?
- It was good.

1570
02:03:48.240 --> 02:03:50.080
But I'll tell you something.

1571
02:03:50.160 --> 02:03:53.760
I want us to stay in here
for the rest of the trip.

1572
02:03:58.120 --> 02:04:00.760
Was that Meredith?

1573
02:04:02.200 --> 02:04:04.040
